{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Faith & Devotion","subcategory":"Zen Buddhism","audienceTags":["tradition:zen","tradition:buddhism","theme:mindfulness","theme:impermanence","audience:meditation","audience:morning"],"sortPriority":50,"groupingLevels":["author"],"groupingLabels":["Teacher"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Zen_Classics.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Zen Masters","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","sourceId":"zenTexts","displayName":"Zen Masters","version":"2.0","language":"English","edition":"Wikiquote Verified & Public Domain Translations","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":1100,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"zen-1","text":"If you wish to know the Way, you must first of all obtain a settled mind. When the mind is settled, it becomes a mirror.","author":"The Sixth Patriarch","source":"Zen Classics — Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-2","text":"If you cannot find the truth right where you are, where else do you expect to find it?","author":"Huineng","source":"Zen Classics — Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-3","text":"Our original nature is Buddha, and apart from this nature there is no other Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Zen Classics — Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-4","text":"No thought is the essence. No form is the substance. Non-abiding is the fundamental.","author":"Huineng","source":"Zen Classics — Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-5","text":"To become attached to one's own ego — this is the source of all suffering.","author":"Huineng","source":"Zen Classics — Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-6","text":"In walking, just walk. In sitting, just sit. Above all, don't wobble.","author":"Master Yun-men","source":"Zen Classics — Blue Cliff Record","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-7","text":"Every day is a good day.","author":"Master Yun-men","source":"Zen Classics — Blue Cliff Record","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-8","text":"Does a dog have Buddha-nature? Mu!","author":"Zhaozhou","source":"Zen Classics — Blue Cliff Record","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-9","text":"If you meet the Buddha on the road, kill the Buddha.","author":"Master Xuefeng","source":"Zen Classics — Blue Cliff Record","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-10","text":"The whole body is sickness.","author":"Baofu","source":"Zen Classics — Blue Cliff Record","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-11","text":"If you meet the Buddha, kill the Buddha. If you meet a patriarch, kill the patriarch. This is the only way to liberation.","author":"Linji","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-12","text":"To study the Way is to study the self. To study the self is to forget the self. To forget the self is to be enlightened by all things.","author":"Dogen","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-13","text":"Do not follow the ideas of others, but learn to listen to the voice within yourself.","author":"Dogen","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-14","text":"The foolish reject what they see, not what they think. The wise reject what they think, not what they see.","author":"Huang-po","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-15","text":"All the Buddhas and all sentient beings are nothing but the One Mind, beside which nothing exists.","author":"Huang-po","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-16","text":"Before enlightenment, chop wood, carry water. After enlightenment, chop wood, carry water.","author":"Joshu","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-17","text":"Right now you are living in the Unborn. If there is no thought of worry, the Buddha-mind is manifested right there.","author":"Bankei","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-18","text":"One instant is eternity; eternity is the now.","author":"Huangbo Xiyun","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-19","text":"There is no fixed dharma which the Tathagata teaches.","author":"Linji","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-20","text":"There are those who, upon realizing that 'the self' is without substance, think this calls for despair. Far from it. The realization that you are without a fixed, limited self means that as you are, right now, you are unlimited.","author":"Dogen","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-21","text":"The mind is like a mirror — it should reflect all things without retaining any.","author":"Huineng","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-22","text":"Be a light unto yourself. Betake yourselves to no external refuge. Hold fast to the Truth.","author":"Rinzai","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-23","text":"Seeking is itself the problem. You are already it. Just recognize it.","author":"Linji","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-24","text":"If you cannot find the truth right where you are, where else do you expect to find it?","author":"Dogen","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-25","text":"The Great Way is not difficult for those who have no preferences. When love and hate are both absent, everything becomes clear and undisguised.","author":"Sengcan","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-26","text":"Do not search for the truth; only cease to cherish opinions.","author":"Sengcan","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-27","text":"My supernatural power and marvelous activity: drawing water and carrying firewood.","author":"Layman Pang","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-28","text":"This very mind is Buddha.","author":"Mazu Daoyi","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-29","text":"The ordinary mind is the Way.","author":"Nanquan","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-30","text":"Have you eaten your rice? Then go wash your bowl. That is all.","author":"Joshu","source":"Zen Classics — Zen Sayings","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000031","text":"Many roads lead to the Path, but basically there are only two: reason and practice.","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000032","text":"Neither gods nor men can forsee when an evil deed will bear its fruit.","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000033","text":"Trying to find a buddha or enlightenment is like trying to grab space. Space has a name but no form. It's not something you can pick up or put down. And you certainly can't grab it. Beyond this mind you'll never see a buddha. The buddha is a product of your mind. Why look for a buddha beyond this mind?","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000034","text":"To find a buddha, you have to see your nature. Whoever sees his nature is a buddha. If you don't see your nature, invoking buddhas, reciting sutras, making offerings, and keeping precepts are all useless. Invoking buddha's results in good karma, reciting sutras results in a good memory; keeping precepts results in a good rebirth, and making offerings results in future blessings–but no buddha.","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000035","text":"Unless they see their nature, how can people call themselves buddhas? They're liars who deceive others into entering the realm of devils. Unless they see their nature, their preaching of the Twelve-fold Canon is nothing but the preaching of devils. Their allegiance is to Mara, not to the Buddha. Unable to distinguish white from black, how can they escape birth and death?","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000036","text":"The essence of the Way is detachment. And the goal of those who practice is freedom from appearances.","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000037","text":"Seeing through the mundane and witnessing the sublime is less than an eye-blink away. Realization is now. Why worry about gray hair?","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000038","text":"達磨面壁。二祖立雪斷臂云。弟子心未安。乞師安心。磨云。將心來。與汝安。祖云。覓心了不可得。磨云。為汝安心竟。","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000039","text":"舉梁武帝問達摩大師：「如何是聖諦第一義？」摩雲：「廓然無聖！」帝曰：「對朕者誰？」摩雲：「不識。」帝不契，達摩遂渡江至魏。","author":"Bodhidharma","source":"Bodhidharma","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000040","text":"A perception, sudden as blinking, that subject and object are one, will lead to a deeply mysterious understanding; and by this understanding you will awaken to the truth.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000041","text":"The foolish reject what they see and not what they think; the wise reject what they think and not what they see.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000042","text":"Sending the Buddha in search of the Buddha, grasping the mind with the mind, they may exhaust themselves in striving for an entire eon but will never get it. They do not understand that if they cease their thoughts and end their thinking, the Buddha will automatically be present.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000043","text":"Therefore, the bodhisattva’s mind is like space, which is completely detached from everything. “Past mental states are imperceptible”: this is detachment from the past. “Present mental states are imperceptible”: this is detachment from the present. “Future mental states are imperceptible”: this is detachment from the future. This is called complete detachment from the three periods of time.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000044","text":"The most important thing is not to maintain the text or form an interpretation of a single [individual] case or a single teaching. Why? There is truly no definitive Dharma that the Tathāgata can preach. In our school we do not discuss these matters (i.e., the doctrines of Buddhism). You should simply understand that we do nothing else but stop the mind. There is no use in thinking about this and that.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000045","text":"[The master] entered the hall and said: Rather than the hundred varieties of erudition, to be without seeking is primary. A religious person is someone who does nothing and is truly without the numerous types of mind. There is also no meaning that can be preached. There’s nothing else, so you may go.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000046","text":"念念不見一切相，莫認前後三際，前際無去，今際無住，後際無來，安然端坐，任運不拘，方名解脫。","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000047","text":"When thoughts arise, then do all things arise. When thoughts vanish, then do all things vanish.","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000048","text":"Apophatic theology (negative theology)","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000049","text":"Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite","author":"Huang Po","source":"Huangbo Xiyun","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000050","text":"Coming, going, the waterbirds don't leave a trace don't follow a path.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000051","text":"But do not ask me where I am going, As I travel in this limitless world, Where every step I take is my home.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000052","text":"As I study both the exoteric and the esoteric schools of Buddhism, they maintain that human beings are endowed with Dharma-nature by birth. If this is the case, why did the Buddhas of all ages — undoubtedly in possession of enlightenment — find it necessary to seek enlightenment and engage in spiritual practice?","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000053","text":"The primordial Buddhas are saying,","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000054","text":"It is only due to a lack of heart for the Way and a lack of skill in handling their daily conduct that people become vainly tied to fame and gain.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000055","text":"Zazen is the ultimate practice. This is indeed the True Self. The Buddhadharma is not to be sought outside of this.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000056","text":"Just practice good, do good for others, without thinking of making yourself known so that you may gain reward. Really bring benefit to others, gaining nothing for yourself. This is the primary requisite for breaking free of attachments to the Self.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000057","text":"When other sects speak well of Zen, the first thing that they praise is its poverty.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000058","text":"Something you want badly enough can always be gained. No matter how fierce the enemy, how remote the beautiful lady, or how carefully guarded the treasure, there is always a means to the goal for the earnest seeker. The unseen help of the guardian gods of heaven and earth assure fulfillment.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000059","text":"Yet you must not cling to the words of the old sages either; they, too, may not be right. Even if you believe them, you should be alert so that, in the event that something superior comes along, you may follow that.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000060","text":"Because monks come from the midst of purity, they consider as good and pure what does not arouse desire among other people.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000061","text":"Students of the Way must not study Buddhism for the sake of themselves. They must study Buddhism only for the sake of Buddhism. The key to this is to renounce both body and mind without holding anything back and to offer them to the great sea of Buddhism.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000062","text":"People who truly follow the Way would do well to conceal the fact that they are Buddhists.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000063","text":"Students today should begrudge every moment of time. This dewlike life fades away; time speeds swiftly. In this short life of ours, avoid involvement in superfluous things and just study the Way.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000064","text":"Just study Buddhism. Don't follow the sentiments of the world.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000065","text":"If he cannot stop the mind that seeks after fame and profit, he will spend his life without finding peace.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000066","text":"Students, when you want to say something, think about it three times before you say it. Speak only if your words will benefit yourselves and others. Do not speak if it brings no benefit.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000067","text":"Buddhas and Ancestors continuously maintain ocean mudra samadhi. While swimming in this samadhi, they expound, realize, practice.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000068","text":"In the great way of going beyond, no endeavor is complete without being one with myriad things. This is ocean mudra samadhi.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000069","text":"Therefore, you must stop comprehending the conduct of investigating words and chasing discourses. You must learn to step backward to turn your light around to reflect on yourself. Mind and body will naturally fall away and your original face will manifest itself. If you wish to attain suchness, devote yourself to suchness at once.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000070","text":"All the Buddhas, whether in this world or in other quarters, in the western heaven (India) or the eastern earth (China), equally held the Buddha-seal and altogether enjoyed the supreme style. They were fully devoted to this total sitting (shikantaza) and were totally installed in this unmoved state. Even though there are a thousand differences and a million nuances, they engaged devotedly in practicing zazen and realizing the Way.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000071","text":"Furthermore, form and substance are like dew on a blade of grass, and fleeting life is as a flash of lightning, instantly emptied and immediately lost.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000072","text":"A collection of dharma texts translated by Ven. Anzan Hoshin roshi. Various Dogen texts here.","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000073","text":"The Shobogenzo at Terebess Asia Online","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000074","text":"Chapters of the Shobogenzo translated by the Soto Zen Text Project","author":"Dogen","source":"Dōgen","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000075","text":"Be a master everywhere and wherever you stand is your true place. (Translator unsourced.)","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000076","text":"The local officials invited Linji to preach. Linji went up to the teaching hall and said: “Today I have no alternative but to bend to human sentiment—thus I have ascended to this seat [to preach]. By the standards of the Zen school, when you attempt to extol the great matter [of enlightenment], you simply cannot open your mouth. There’s no place for you to get a foothold.”","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000077","text":"Worthy people, we must value the time. [You are wasting your chance] if you just intend to ‘study Zen’ and ‘study the Path’ as superficial adherents running busily back and forth, getting to recognize terms and phrases, seeking ‘buddhas,’ seeking ‘patriarchs,’ seeking ‘enlightened teachers’ [as you conceive of them]. You only have one father and mother: what else are you seeking? You should reflect back on yourself and see them.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000078","text":"Someone asked: “What are enlightenment and delusion?”Linji said: “A moment when your mind is in doubt is delusion. If you can comprehend that the myriad phenomena are unborn, that [deluded] mind is like an illusory transformation, so that you are everywhere pure, this is enlightenment. So enlightenment and delusion are the two objects, defilement and purity.”","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000079","text":"In my view, there are no buddhas and no sentient beings, no ancient and no modern. Those who attain, attain without cultivation, without realization, without gain, and without loss, for them there is never anything else but reality. ‘Even if there is anything that goes beyond this, I would say that it is like a dream or a magical illusion.’ This is what I am saying.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000080","text":"Outside of mind there is nothing, and what is within mind is also unattainable. What are you looking for? All of you people everywhere talk of having cultivation and having realization, but don’t make this mistake. Even if you gain something from cultivation, it is just the karma of birth and death.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000081","text":"Even the multi-part scriptural teachings of the three vehicles are just old paper for wiping away dirt. Buddha is an illusion, an apparition. The ancestral teachers were just old monks.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000082","text":"Good people, the real Buddha is formless; the real Dharma has no marks. The way you are acting is to erect models and patterns based upon the illusory transformations [which were provisionally put forward in the Buddhist teachings]. Even if you get something from this, you are all wild fox spirits. This is not real Buddhism at all, but the view of outsiders.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000083","text":"If you love the holy and hate the ordinary, you float and sink in the sea of birth and death. Affliction exists because of mind: if you have no mind, how can affliction hold you? If you do not try to discriminate and grasp forms, naturally you find the Path that instant.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000084","text":"I tell you, there is no Buddha, no Dharma, no cultivation, no realization. What are you trying to find this way as a shallow adherent? Blind people [who reify these concepts] are placing a head upon a head [imposing objects of seeking upon spontaneous reality].","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000085","text":"Good people, the physical body composed of the four great elements is impermanent. [All the parts of your body], your spleen and stomach and liver and hair and nails and teeth, just reveal the emptiness of all things.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000086","text":"An ancient said that if you call it a thing, you miss the mark. Just look for yourself: what else is there? Talk could go on forever: each of you must personally make the effort.","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000087","text":"The Zen Teaching of Rinzai","author":"Linji Yixuan","source":"Linji Yixuan","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000088","text":"Don`t despise a beginner,\" said I, \"if you are a seeker of supreme enlightenment. You should know that the lowest class may have the sharpest wit, while the highest may be in want of intelligence. If you slight others, you commit a very great sin.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000089","text":"For him who does not know his own mind there is no use learning Buddhism. On the other hand, if he knows his own mind and sees intuitively his own nature, he is a Hero, a 'Teacher of gods and men', 'Buddha'.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000090","text":"As to the Dharma, this is transmitted from heart to heart, and the recipient must realize it by his own efforts.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000091","text":"The wisdom of enlightenment is inherent in every one of us. It is because of the delusion under which our mind works that we fail to realize it ourselves, and that we have to seek the advice and the guidance of enlightened ones before we can know our own Essence of Mind.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000092","text":"You should know that so far as Buddha-nature is concerned, there is no difference between an enlightened man and an ignorant one. What makes the difference is that one realizes it, while the other is ignorant of it.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000093","text":"Our very nature is Buddha, and apart from this nature there is no other Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000094","text":"What the ignorant merely talk about, wise men put into actual practice with their mind.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000095","text":"A foolish passing thought makes one an ordinary man, while an enlightened second thought makes one a Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000096","text":"To illumine our gloomy tabernacle, which is stained by defilement,We should constantly set up the Light of Wisdom.Erroneous views keep us in defilementWhile right views remove us from it,But when we are in a position to discard both of themWe are then absolutely pure.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000097","text":"Within our impure mind the pure one is to be found.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000098","text":"He who does not know his own Essence of Mind, and is under the delusion that Buddhahood can be attained by outward religious rites is called the slow-witted.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000099","text":"A gleam of enlightenment is enough to make any living being the equal of a Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000100","text":"To know our mind is to obtain liberation.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000101","text":"The mind should be framed in such a way that it will be independent of external or internal objects, at liberty to come or go, free from attachment and thoroughly enlightened without the least beclouding.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000102","text":"All sutras and scriptures of the Mahayana and Hinayana Schools, as well as the twelve sections of the canonical writings, were provided to suit the different needs and temperaments of various people. It is upon the principle that Prajna is latent in every man that the doctrines expounded in these books are established.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000103","text":"The wise preach to the ignorant when the latter ask them to do so. Through this the ignorant may attain sudden enlightenment, and their mind thereby becomes illuminated. Then they are no longer different from the wise men.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000104","text":"Our Essence of Mind is intrinsically pure, and if we knew our mind and realized what our nature is, all of us would attain Buddhahood.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000105","text":"The wisdom of the past, the present and the future Buddhas as well as the teachings of the twelve sections of the Canon are immanent in our mind; but in case we fail to enlighten ourselves, we have to seek the guidance of the pious and learned ones. On the other hand, those who enlighten themselves need no extraneous help. It is wrong to insist upon the idea that without the advice of the pious and learned we cannot obtain liberation.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000106","text":"If we find fault with othersWe ourselves are also in the wrong.When other people are in the wrong, we should ignore it,For it is wrong for us to find fault.By getting rid of the habit of fault-findingWe cut off a source of defilement.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000107","text":"The Kingdom of Buddha is in this world,Within which enlightenment is to be sought.To seek enlightenment by separating from this worldIs as absurd as to search for a rabbit's horn.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000108","text":"Kalpa after kalpa a man may be under delusion,But once enlightened it takes him only a moment to attain Buddhahood.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000109","text":"When the people of the East commit a sin, they recite the name of Amitabha and pray to be born in the West; but in the case of sinners who are natives of the West, where should they pray to be born? Ordinary men and ignorant people understand neither the Essence of Mind nor the Pure Land within themselves, so they wish to be born in the East or the West. But to the enlightened everywhere is the same. As the Buddha said, \"No matter where they happen to be, they are always happy and comfortable.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000110","text":"We should work for Buddhahood within the Essence of Mind, and we should not look for it apart from ourselves. He who is kept in ignorance of his Essence of Mind is an ordinary being. He who is enlightened in his Essence of Mind is a Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000111","text":"By amending our mistakes, we get wisdom.By defending our faults, we betray an unsound mind.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000112","text":"Argument is unnecessary for an enlightened disciple. ... Argument implies a desire to win, strengthens egotism, and ties us to the belief in the idea of a self.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000113","text":"All things - good or bad, beautiful or ugly - should be treated as void. Even in time of disputes and quarrels we should treat our intimates and our enemies alike and never think of retaliation. In the exercise of our thinking faculty, let the past be dead. If we allow our thoughts, past, present, and future, to link up in a series, we put ourselves under restraint. On the other hand, if we never let our mind attach to anything, we shall gain emancipation.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000114","text":"Our mind should stand aloof from circumstances, and on no account should we allow them to influence the function of our mind. But it is a great mistake to suppress our mind from all thinking.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000115","text":"If we are attached to outer objects, our inner mind will be perturbed. When we are free from attachment to all outer objects, the mind will be in peace. Our Essence of Mind is intrinsically pure, and the reason why we are perturbed is because we allow ourselves to be carried away by the circumstances we are in.He who is able to keep his mind unperturbed, irrespective of circumstances, has attained Samadhi.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000116","text":"When our mind clings to neither good nor evil we should take care not to let it dwell upon vacuity, or remain in a state of inertia. Rather should we enlarge our study and broaden our knowledge, so that we can know our own mind, understand thoroughly the principles of Buddhism, be congenial to others in our dealings with them, get rid of the idea of \"self\" and that of \"being\", and realize that up to the time when we attain Bodhi the \"true nature\" (or Essence of Mind) is always immutable.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000117","text":"May we ... be always free from the taints of ignorance and delusion. We repent of all our sins and evil deeds committed under delusion or in ignorance. May they be expiated at once and may they never arise again.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000118","text":"On account of ignorance and delusion, common people do not realize that in repentance they have not only to feel sorry for their past sins but also to refrain from sinning in the future. Since they take no heed of their future conduct they commit new sins before the past are expiated. How can we call this \"repentance\"?","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000119","text":"The sutra distinctly says that we should take refuge in the Buddha within ourselves; it does not suggest that we should take refuge in other Buddhas. Moreover, if we do not take refuge in the Buddha within ourselves, there is no other place for us to retreat.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000120","text":"To attain enlightenment by our own efforts and to practice by ourself the goodness inherent in our Essence of Mind is a genuine case of \"Taking Refuge\".","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000121","text":"Why not get rid of the sin within our own mind, for this is true repentance.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000122","text":"Buddha-knowledge is the Buddha-knowledge of your own mind and not that of any other Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000123","text":"Being infatuated by sense-objects, and thereby shutting themselves from their own light, all sentient beings, tormented by outer circumstances and inner vexations, act voluntarily as slaves to their own desires. Seeing this, our Lord Buddha had to rise from his Samadhi in order to exhort them with earnest preaching of various kinds to suppress their desires and to refrain from seeking happiness from without, so that they might become the equals of Buddha.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000124","text":"To see, to hear, and to recite the sutra is the small vehicle. To know the Dharma and to understand its meaning is the middle vehicle. To put the Dharma into actual practice is the great vehicle. To understand thoroughly all Dharmas, to have absorbed them completely, to be free from all attachments, to be above phenomena, and to be in possession of nothing, is the Supreme Vehicle.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000125","text":"It is for a sole object, a sole aim, verily a lofty object and a lofty aim that the Buddha appears in this world. Now that sole object, that sole aim, that lofty object, that lofty aim referred to is the \"sight\" of Buddha-Knowledge.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000126","text":"It was to ordinary men, not to other Buddhas, that Buddha Gautama preached this Sutra.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000127","text":"To start by seeking for Trikaya and the four Prajnas is to take an entirely wrong course (for being inherent in us they are to be realized and not to be sought). To try to \"grasp\" or \"confine\" them is to go against their intrinsic nature.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000128","text":"If I tell you that I have a system of Law &#91;Dharma&#93; to transmit to others, I am cheating you. What I do to my disciples is to liberate them from their own bondage with such devices as the case may need.","author":"Huineng","source":"Platform Sutra","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000129","text":"This mind is an uncertain thing. This body is uncertain. Together they are impermanent. Together they are a source of suffering. Together they are devoid of self. These, the Buddha pointed out, are neither a being, nor a person, nor a self, nor a soul, nor us, nor they. They are merely elements: earth, water, fire and wind. Elements only!","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000130","text":"When the mind sees this, it will rid itself of attachment which holds that \"I\" am beautiful, \"I\" am good, \"I\" am evil, \"I\" am suffering, \"I\" have, \"I\" this or \"I\" that. You will experience a state of unity, for you'll have seen that all of mankind is basically the same. There is no \"I.\" There are only elements.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000131","text":"So don't be in a hurry and try to push or rush your practice. Do your meditation gently and gradually step by step. In regard to peacefulness, if you want to become peaceful, then accept it; if you don't become peaceful, then accept that also. That's the nature of the mind. We must find our own practice and persistently keep at it.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000132","text":"If we have that presence of mind then whatever work we do will be the very tool which enables us to know right and wrong continually. There’s plenty of time to meditate, we just don’t fully understand the practice, that’s all. While sleeping we breathe, eating we breathe, don’t we? Why don’t we have time to meditate? Wherever we are we breathe. If we think like this then our life has as much value as our breath, wherever we are we have time.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000133","text":"Actually this practice is just about the mind and its feelings. It’s not something that you have to run after or struggle for. Breathing continues while working. Nature takes care of the natural processes—all we have to do is try to be aware. Just to keep trying, going inwards to see clearly. Meditation is like this.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000134","text":"One who studies and doesn’t practice is like a ladle of soup pot. It’s in the pot every day but it doesn’t know the flavor of the soup. If you don’t practice, even if you study till the day you die, you won’t know the taste of Freedom!","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000135","text":"The real basis of Buddhism is full knowledge of the truth of reality. If one knows this truth then no teaching is necessary. If one doesn’t know, even if he listens to the teaching, he doesn’t really hear.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000136","text":"The mind and feeling are just like oil and water; they are in the same bottle but they don’t mix. Even if we are sick or in pain, we still know the feeling as feeling, the mind as mind. We know the painful or comfortable states but we don’t identify with them. We stay only with peace: the peace beyond both comfort and pain.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000137","text":"Simply keep putting everything down, and know that that is what you are doing. You don't need to be always checking up on yourself, worrying about things like \"How much samādhi\"—it will always be the right amount. Whatever arises in your practice, let it go; know it all as uncertain, impermanent. Remember that! It's all uncertain. Be finished with all of it. This is the Way that will take you to the source—to your Original Mind.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000138","text":"Therefore the practice is like a key, the key of meditation. If we have the right key in our hand, no matter how tightly the lock is closed, when we take the key and turn it the lock falls open. If we have no key we can’t open the lock. We will never know what it is in the trunk.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000139","text":"The source of all good, evil, weal and harm lies with actions, speech and thoughts. Did you bring your actions, speech and thoughts with you today? Or have you left them at home? This is where you must look, right here. You don’t have to look very far away. Look at your actions, speech and thoughts. Look to see if your conduct is faulty or not.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000140","text":"The value of Dhamma isn’t to be found in books. Those are just the external appearances of Dhamma, they’re not the realization of Dhamma as a personal experience. If you realize the Dhamma you realize your own mind, you see the truth there. When the truth becomes apparent it cuts off the stream of delusion.","author":"Ajahn Chah","source":"Ajahn Chah","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"zen-ext-000141","text":"THE CONSTITUTION OF JAPAN, 1946","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000142","text":"Promulgated on November 3, 1946; Put into effect on May 3, 1947.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000143","text":"Government is a sacred trust of the people, the authority for which is derived from the people, the powers of which are exercised by the representatives of the people, and the benefits of which are enjoyed by the people.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000144","text":"This is a universal principle of mankind upon which this Constitution is founded.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000145","text":"We reject and revoke all constitutions, laws, ordinances, and rescripts in conflict herewith.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000146","text":"We, the Japanese people, desire peace for all time and are deeply conscious of the high ideals controlling human relationship, and we have determined to preserve our security and existence, trusting in the justice and faith of the peace-loving peoples of the world.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000147","text":"We desire to occupy an honored place in an international society striving for the preservation of peace, and the banishment of tyranny and slavery, oppression and intolerance for all time from the earth.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000148","text":"We recognize that all peoples of the world have the right to live in peace, free from fear and want.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000149","text":"We believe that no nation is responsible to itself alone, but that laws of political morality are universal; and that obedience to such laws is incumbent upon all nations who would sustain their own sovereignty and justify their sovereign relationship with other nations.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000150","text":"We, the Japanese people, pledge our national honor to accomplish these high ideals and purposes with all our resources.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000151","text":"Article 1. The Emperor shall be the symbol of the State and of the unity of the people, deriving his position from the will of the people with whom resides sovereign power.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000152","text":"Article 2. The Imperial Throne shall be dynastic and succeeded to in accordance with the Imperial House law passed by the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000153","text":"Article 3. The advice and approval of the Cabinet shall be required for all acts of the Emperor in matters of state, and the Cabinet shall be responsible therefor.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000154","text":"Article 4. The Emperor shall perform only such acts in matters of state as are provided for in this Constitution and he shall not have powers related to government","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000155","text":"(2) The Emperor may delegate the performance of his acts in matters of state as may be provided by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000156","text":"Article 5. When, in accordance with the Imperial House law, a Regency is established, the Regent shall perform his acts in matter of state in the Emperor's name. In this case, paragraph one of the article will be applicable.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000157","text":"Article 6. The Emperor shall appoint the Prime Minister as designated by the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000158","text":"(2) The Emperor shall appoint the Chief Judge of the Supreme Court as designated by the Cabinet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000159","text":"Article 7. The Emperor, with the advice and approval of the Cabinet, shall perform the following acts in makers of state on behalf of the people:","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000160","text":"(i) Promulgation of amendments of the constitution, laws, cabinet orders and treaties;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000161","text":"(iii) Dissolution of the House of Representatives;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000162","text":"(iv) Proclamation of general election of members of the Diet;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000163","text":"(v) Attestation of the appointment and dismissal of Ministers of State and other officials as provided for by law, and of full powers and credentials of Ambassadors and Ministers;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000164","text":"(vi) Attestation of general and special amnesty, commutation of punishment, reprieve, and restoration of rights;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000165","text":"(viii) Attestation of instruments of ratification and other diplomatic documents as provided for by law;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000166","text":"(ix) Receiving foreign ambassadors and ministers;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000167","text":"(x) Performance of ceremonial functions.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000168","text":"Article 8. No property can be given to, or received by, the Imperial House, nor can any gifts be made therefrom, without the authorization of the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000169","text":"CHAPTER II. RENUNCIATION OF WAR","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000170","text":"Article 9. Aspiring sincerely to an international peace based on justice and order, the Japanese people forever renounce war as a sovereign right of the nation and the threat or use of force as a mean of settling international disputes.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000171","text":"(2) In order to accomplish the aim of the preceding paragraph, land, sea, and air forces, as well as other war potential, will never be maintained. The right of belligerency of the state will not be recognized.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000172","text":"CHAPTER III. RIGHTS AND DUTIES OF THE PEOPLE","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000173","text":"Article 10. The conditions necessary for being a Japanese national shall be determined by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000174","text":"Article 11. The people shall not be prevented from enjoying any of the fundamental human rights. These fundamental human rights guaranteed to the people by this Constitution shall be conferred upon the people of this and future generations as eternal and inviolate rights.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000175","text":"Article 12. The freedoms and rights guaranteed to the people by this Constitution shall be maintained by the constant endeavor of the people, who shall refrain from any abuse of these freedoms and rights and shall always be responsible for utilizing them for the public welfare.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000176","text":"Article 13. All of the people shall be respected as individuals. Their right to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness shall, to the extent that it does not interfere with the public welfare, be the supreme consideration in legislation and in other governmental affairs.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000177","text":"Article 14. All of the people are equal under the law and there shall be no discrimination in political, economic or social relations because of race, creed, sex, social status or family origin.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000178","text":"(2) Peers and peerage shall not be recognized.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000179","text":"(3) No privilege shall accompany any award of honor, decoration or any distinction, nor shall any such award be valid beyond the lifetime of the individual who now holds or hereafter may receive it.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000180","text":"Article 15. The people have the inalienable right to choose their public officials and to dismiss them.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000181","text":"(2) All public officials are servants of the whole community and not of any group thereof.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000182","text":"(3) Universal adult suffrage is guaranteed with regard to the election of public officials.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000183","text":"(4) In all elections, secrecy of the ballot shall not be violated. A voter shall not be answerable, publicly or privately, for the choice he has made.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000184","text":"Every person shall have the right of peaceful petition for the redress of damage, for the removal of public officials, for the enactment, repeal or amendment of law, ordinances or regulations and for other matters, nor shall any person be in any way discriminated against sponsoring such a petition.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000185","text":"Article 17. Every person may sue for redress as provided by law from the State or a public entity, in case he has suffered damage through illegal act of any public official.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000186","text":"Article 18. No person shall be held in bondage of any kind. Involuntary servitude, except as punishment for crime, is prohibited.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000187","text":"Article 19. Freedom of thought and conscience shall not be violated.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000188","text":"Article 20. Freedom of religion is guaranteed to all. No religious organization shall receive any privileges from the State nor exercise any political authority.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000189","text":"(2) No person shall be compelled to take part in any religious acts, celebration, rite or practice.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000190","text":"(3) The state and its organs shall refrain from religious education or any other religious activity.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000191","text":"Article 21. Freedom of assembly and association as well as speech, press and all other forms of expression are guaranteed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000192","text":"(2) No censorship shall be maintained, nor shall the secrecy of any means of communication be violated.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000193","text":"Article 22. Every person shall have freedom to choose and change his residence and to choose his occupation to the extent that it does not interfere with the public welfare.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000194","text":"(2) Freedom of all persons to move to a foreign country and to divest themselves of their nationality shall be inviolate.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000195","text":"Article 23. Academic freedom is guaranteed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000196","text":"Article 24. Marriage shall be based only on the mutual consent of both sexes and it shall be maintained through mutual cooperation with the equal rights of husband and wife as a basis.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000197","text":"(2) With regard to choice of spouse, property rights, inheritance, choice of domicile, divorce and other matters pertaining to marriage and the family, laws shall be enacted from the standpoint of individual dignity and the essential equality of the sexes.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000198","text":"Article 25. All people shall have the right to maintain the minimum standards of wholesome and cultured living.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000199","text":"(2) In all spheres of life, the State shall use its endeavors for the promotion and extension of social welfare and security, and of public health.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000200","text":"Article 26. All people shall have the right to receive an equal education correspondent to their ability, as provided by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000201","text":"(2) All people shall be obligated to have all boys and girls under their protection receive ordinary educations as provided for by law. Such compulsory education shall be free.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000202","text":"Article 27. All people shall have the right and the obligation to work.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000203","text":"(2) Standards for wages, hours, rest and other working conditions shall be fixed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000204","text":"(3) Children shall not be exploited.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000205","text":"Article 28. The right of workers to organize and to bargain and act collectively is guaranteed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000206","text":"Article 29. The right to own or to hold property is inviolable.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000207","text":"(2) Property rights shall be defined by law, in conformity with the public welfare.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000208","text":"(3) Private property may be taken for public use upon just compensation therefor.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000209","text":"Article 30. The people shall be liable to taxations as provided by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000210","text":"Article 31. No person shall be deprived of life or liberty, nor shall any other criminal penalty be imposed, except according to procedure established by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000211","text":"Article 32. No person shall be denied the right of access to the courts.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000212","text":"Article 33. No person shall be apprehended except upon warrant issued by a competent judicial officer which specifies the offense with which the person is charged, unless he is apprehended, the offense being committed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000213","text":"The right of all persons to be secure in their homes, papers and effects against entries, searches and seizures shall not be impaired except upon warrant issued for adequate cause and particularly describing the place to be searched and things to be seized, or except as provided by Article 33.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000214","text":"(2) Each search or seizure shall be made upon separate warrant Issued by a competent judicial officer.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000215","text":"Article 36. The infliction of torture by any public officer and cruel punishments are absolutely forbidden.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000216","text":"Article 39. In all criminal cases the accused shall enjoy the right to a speedy and public trial by an impartial tribunal.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000217","text":"(2) He shall be permitted full opportunity to examine all witnesses, and he shall have the right of compulsory process for obtaining witnesses on his behalf at public expense.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000218","text":"(3) At all times the accused shall have the assistance of competent counsel who shall, if the accused is unable to secure the same by his own efforts, be assigned to his use by the State.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000219","text":"Article 38. No person shall be compelled to testify against himself.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000220","text":"(2) Confession made under compulsion, torture or threat, or after prolonged arrest or detention shall not be admitted in evidence.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000221","text":"(3) No person shall be convicted or punished in cases where the only proof against him is his own confession.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000222","text":"Article 39. No person shall be held criminally liable for an act which was lawful at the time it was committed, or of which he has been acquitted, nor shall he be placed in double jeopardy.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000223","text":"Article 40. Any person, in case he is acquitted after he has been arrested or detained, may sue the State for redress as provided by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000224","text":"Article 41. The Diet shall be the highest organ of state power, and shall be the sole law-making organ of the State.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000225","text":"Article 42. The Diet shall consist of two Houses, namely the House of Representatives and the House of Councillors.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000226","text":"Article 43. Both Houses shall consist of elected members, representative of all the people.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000227","text":"(2) The number of the members of each House shall be fixed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000228","text":"Article 44. The qualifications of members of both Houses and their electors shall be fixed by law. However, there shall be no discrimination because of race, creed, sex, social status, family origin, education, property or income.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000229","text":"Article 45. The term of office of members of the House of Representatives shall be four years. However, the term shall be terminated before the full term is up in case the House of Representatives is dissolved.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000230","text":"Article 46. The term of office of members of the House of Councillors shall be six years, and election for half the members shall take place every three years.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000231","text":"Article 47. Electoral districts, method of voting and other matters pertaining to the method of election of members of both Houses shall be fixed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000232","text":"Article 48. No person shall be permitted to be a member of both Houses simultaneously.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000233","text":"Article 49. Members of both Houses shall receive appropriate annual payment from the national treasury in accordance with law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000234","text":"Article 50. Except in cases provided by law, members of both Houses shall be exempt from apprehension while the Diet is in session, and any members apprehended before the opening of the session shall be freed during the term of the session upon demand of the House.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000235","text":"Article 51. Members of both Houses shall not be held liable outside the House for speeches, debates or votes cast inside the House.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000236","text":"Article 52. An ordinary session of the Diet shall be convoked once per year.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000237","text":"Article 53. The Cabinet may determine to convoke extraordinary sessions of the Diet. When a quarter or more of the total members of either house makes the demand, the Cabinet must determine on such convocation.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000238","text":"Article 54. When the House of Representatives is dissolved, there must be a general election of members of the House of Representatives within forty (40) days from the date of dissolution, and the Diet must be convoked within thirty (30) days from the date of the election.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000239","text":"(2) When the House of Representatives is dissolved, the House of Councillors is closed at the same time. However, the Cabinet may in time of national emergency convoke the House of Councillors in emergency session.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000240","text":"(3) Measures taken at such session as mentioned in the proviso of the preceding paragraph shall be provisional and shall become null and void unless agreed to by the House of Representatives within a period of ten (10) days after the opening of the next session of the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000241","text":"Article 55. Each House shall judge disputes related to qualifications of its members. However, in order to deny a seat to any member, it is necessary to pass a resolution by a majority of two-thirds or more of the members present.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000242","text":"Article 56. Business cannot be transacted in either House unless one third or more of total membership is present.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000243","text":"(2) All matters shall be decided, in each House, by a majority of those present, except as elsewhere provided in the Constitution, and in case of a tie, the presiding officer shall decide the issue.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000244","text":"Article 57. Deliberation in each House shall be public. However, a secret meeting may be held where a majority of two-thirds or more of those members present passes a resolution therefor.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000245","text":"(2) Each House shall keep a record of proceedings. This record shall be published and given general circulation, excepting such parts of proceedings of secret session as may be deemed to require secrecy.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000246","text":"(3) Upon demand of one-fifth or more of the members present, votes of the members on any matter shall be recorded in the minutes.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000247","text":"Article 58. Each house shall select its own president and other officials.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000248","text":"(2) Each House shall establish its rules pertaining to meetings, proceedings and internal discipline, and may punish members for disorderly conduct. However, in order to expel a member, a majority of two-thirds or more of those members present must pass a resolution thereon.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000249","text":"Article 59. A bill becomes a law on passage by both Houses, except as otherwise provided by the Constitution.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000250","text":"(3) The provision of the preceding paragraph does not preclude the House of Representatives from calling for the meeting of a joint committee of both Houses, provided for by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000251","text":"(4) Failure by the House of Councillors to take final action within sixty (60) days after receipt of a bill passed by the House of Representatives, time in recess excepted, may be determined by the House of Representatives to constitute a rejection of the said bill by the House of Councillors.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000252","text":"Article 60. The Budget must first be submitted to the House of Representatives.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000253","text":"Article 61. The second paragraph of the preceding article applies also to the Diet approval required for the conclusion of treaties.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000254","text":"Article 62. Each House may conduct investigations in relation to government, and may demand the presence and testimony of witnesses, and the production of records.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000255","text":"Article 63. The Prime Minister and other Ministers of State may, at any time, appear in either House for the purpose of speaking on bills, regardless of whether they are members of the House or not. They must appear when their presence is required in order to give answers or explanations.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000256","text":"Article 64. The Diet shall set up an impeachment court from among the members of both Houses for the purpose of trying judges against whom removal proceedings have been instituted.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000257","text":"(2) Matters relating to impeachment shall be provided by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000258","text":"Article 65. Executive power shall be vested in the Cabinet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000259","text":"Article 66. The Cabinet shall consist of the Prime Minister, who shall be its head, and other Ministers of State, as provided for by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000260","text":"(2) The Prime Minister and other Minister of State must be civilians.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000261","text":"(3) The Cabinet, in the exercise of executive power, shall be collectively responsible to the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000262","text":"Article 67. The Prime Minister shall be designated from among the members of the Diet by a resolution of the Diet. This designation shall precede all other business.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000263","text":"Article 68. The Prime Minister shall appoint the Ministers of State. However, a majority of their number must be chosen from among the members of the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000264","text":"(2) The Prime Minister may remove the Ministers of State as he chooses.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000265","text":"Article 69. If the House of Representatives passes a non-confidence resolution, or rejects a confidence resolution, the Cabinet shall resign en masse, unless the House of Representatives is dissolved with ten (10) days.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000266","text":"Article 70. When there is a vacancy in the post of Prime Minister, or upon the first convocation of the Diet after a general election of members of the House of Representatives, the Cabinet shall resign en masse.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000267","text":"Article 71. In the cases mentioned in the two preceding articles, the Cabinet shall continue its functions until the time when a new Prime Minister is appointed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000268","text":"Article 72. The Prime Minister, representing the Cabinet, submits bills, reports on general national affairs and foreign relations to the Diet and exercises control and supervision over various administrative branches.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000269","text":"Article 73. The Cabinet, in addition to other general administrative functions, shall perform the following functions:","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000270","text":"(i) Administer the law faithfully; conduct affairs of state;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000271","text":"(iii) Conclude treaties. However, it shall obtain prior or, depending on circumstances, subsequent approval of the Diet;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000272","text":"(iv) Administer the civil service, in accordance with standards established by law;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000273","text":"(v) Prepare the budget, and present it to the Diet;","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000274","text":"(vi) Enact cabinet orders in order to execute the provisions of this Constitution and of the law. However, it cannot include penal provisions in such cabinet orders unless authorized by such law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000275","text":"(vii) Decide on general amnesty, special amnesty, commutation of punishment, reprieve, and restoration of rights.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000276","text":"Article 74. All laws and cabinet orders shall be signed by the competent Minister of state and countersigned by the Prime Minister.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000277","text":"Article 75. The Ministers of state, during their tenure of office, shall not be subject to legal action without the consent of the Prime Minister. However, the right to take that action is not impaired hereby.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000278","text":"Article 76. The whole judicial power is vested in a Supreme Court and in such inferior courts as are established by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000279","text":"(2) No extraordinary tribunal shall be established, nor shall any organ or agency of the Executive be given final judicial power.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000280","text":"(3) All judges shall be independent in the exercise of their conscience and shall be bound only by this Constitution and the laws.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000281","text":"Article 77. The Supreme Court is vested with the rule-making power under which it determines the rules of procedure and of practice, and of matters relating to attorneys, the internal discipline of the courts and the administration of judicial affairs.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000282","text":"(2) Public procurators shall be subject to the rule-making power of the Supreme Court.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000283","text":"(3) The Supreme Court may delegate the power to make rules for inferior courts to such courts.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000284","text":"Article 78. Judges shall not be removed except by public impeachment unless judicially declared mentally or physically incompetent to perform official duties. No disciplinary action against judges shall be administered by any executive organ or agency.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000285","text":"Article 79. The Supreme Court shall consist of a Chief Judge and such number of judges as may be determined by law; all such judges excepting the Chief Judge shall be appointed by the Cabinet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000286","text":"(3) In cases mentioned in the foregoing paragraph, when the majority of the voters favors the dismissal of a judge, he shall be dismissed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000287","text":"(4) Matters pertaining to review shall be prescribed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000288","text":"(5) The judges of the Supreme Court shall of retired upon the attainment of the age as fixed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000289","text":"(6) All such judges shall receive, at regular stated intervals, adequate compensation which shall not be decreased during their terms of office.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000290","text":"The judges of the inferior courts shall be appointed by the Cabinet from a list of persons nominated by the Supreme Court.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000291","text":"All such judges shall hold office for a term of ten (10) years with privilege of reappointment, provided that they shall be retired upon the attainment of the age as fixed by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000292","text":"(2) The judges of the inferior courts shall receive, at regular stated intervals, adequate compensation which shall not be decreased during their terms of office.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000293","text":"Article 81. The Supreme Court is the court of last resort with power to determine the constitutionality of any law, order, regulation or official act.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000294","text":"Article 82. Trials shall be conducted and judgment declared publicly.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000295","text":"Article 83. The power to administer national finances shall be exercised as the Diet shall determine.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000296","text":"Article 84. No new taxes shall be imposed or existing ones modified except by law or under such conditions as law may prescribe.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000297","text":"Article 85. No money shall be expended, nor shall the State obligate itself, except as authorized by the Diet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000298","text":"Article 86. Cabinet shall prepare and submit to the Diet for its consideration and decision a budget for each fiscal year.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000299","text":"Article 87. In order to provide for unforeseen deficiencies in the budget, a reserve fund may be authorized by the Diet to be expended upon the responsibility of the Cabinet.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000300","text":"(2) The Cabinet must get subsequent approval of the Diet for all payments from the reserve fund.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000301","text":"Article 88. All property of the Imperial Household shall belong to the State. All expenses of the Imperial Household shall be appropriated by the Diet in the budget.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000302","text":"Article 89. No public money or other property shall be expended or appropriated for the use, benefit or maintenance of any religious institution or association or for any charitable, educational benevolent enterprises not under the control of public authority.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000303","text":"Article 90. Final accounts of the expenditures and revenues of State shall be audited annually by a Board of Audit and submitted by the Cabinet to the Diet, together with the statement of audit, during the fiscal year immediately following the period covered.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000304","text":"(2) The organization and competency of the Board of Audit shall determined by law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000305","text":"Article 91. At regular intervals and at least annually the Cabinet shall report to the Diet and the people on the state of national finances.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000306","text":"CHAPTER VIII. LOCAL SELF-GOVERNMENT","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000307","text":"Article 92. Regulations concerning organization and operations of local public entities shall be fixed by law in accordance with the principle of local autonomy.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000308","text":"Article 93. The local public entities shall establish assemblies as their deliberative organs, in accordance with law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000309","text":"(2) The chief executive officers of all local public entities, the members of their assemblies, and such other local officials as may be determined by law shall be elected by direct popular vote within their several communities","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000310","text":"Article 94. Local entities shall have the right to manage their property, affairs and administration and to enact their own regulations within law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000311","text":"Article 95. A special law, applicable to one local public entity, cannot be enacted by the Diet without the consent of the majority of the voters of the local public entity concerned, obtained in accordance with law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000312","text":"(2) Amendments when so ratified shall immediately be promulgated by the Emperor in the name of the people, as an integral part of this Constitution.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000313","text":"The fundamental human rights by this Constitution guaranteed to the people of Japan are fruits of the age-old struggle of man to be free; they have survived the many exacting tests for durability and are conferred upon this and future generations in trust, to be held for all time inviolate.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000314","text":"Article 98. This Constitution shall be the supreme law of the nation and no law, ordinance, imperial rescript or other act of government, or part thereof, contrary to the provisions hereof, shall have legal force or validity.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000315","text":"(2) The treaties concluded by Japan and established laws of nations shall be faithfully observed.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000316","text":"Article 99. The Emperor or the Regent as well as Ministers of State, members of the Diet, judges, and all other public officials have the obligation to respect and uphold this Constitution.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000317","text":"CHAPTER XI. SUPPLEMENTARY PROVISIONS","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000318","text":"Article 100. This Constitution shall be enforced as from the day when the period of six months will have elapsed counting from the day of its promulgation.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000319","text":"Article 101. If the House of Councilors is not constituted before the effective date of this Constitution, the House of Representatives shall function as the Diet until such time as the House of Councilors shall be constituted.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000320","text":"Article 102. The term of office for half the members of the House of Councillors serving in the first term under this Constitution shall be three years. Members falling under this category shall be determined in accordance with law.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000321","text":"When, however, successors are elected or appointed under the provisions of this Constitution, they shall forfeit their positions as a matter of course.","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000322","text":"End of Project Gutenberg's The Constitution of Japan, 1946, by Japan","author":"Huang Po","source":"The Huang Po Doctrine of Universal Mind (Blofeld, 1958)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000323","text":"Author of _Daring Wings_ _Circle 4 Patrol","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000324","text":"THE GOLDSMITH PUBLISHING CO. CHICAGO","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000325","text":"------------------------------------------------------------------------","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000326","text":"COPYRIGHT 1932 THE GOLDSMITH PUBLISHING COMPANY Made in U. S. A.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000327","text":"Gray clouds of winter hung over the city as the noon edition of the _Atkinson News_ roared off the press.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000328","text":"Tim Murphy, famous young flying reporter and aviation editor of the _News_, pecked away half-heartedly at his typewriter trying to write a story about a minor automobile accident that had happened a few minutes before in front of the _News_ building.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000329","text":"The raw, damp weather and the lead-colored sky had a depressing effect on Tim. He felt earthbound, restless, and he longed to soar through the clouds in the _Good News_, the trim, fast biplane owned by the paper.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000330","text":"What are you looking so gloomy about?\" asked Ralph Graves, who had been Tim's flying companion on many an aerial adventure.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000331","text":"This weather is enough to give anyone a grouch,\" replied Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000332","text":"Here it is, almost spring, and we have to get a week of sloppy weather that spoils all our plans.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000333","text":"That job of overhauling the _Good News_ and installing the new motor will be done today but it won't do us any good.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000334","text":"With weather like this we won't get any flying assignments.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000335","text":"I know just how you feel,\" sympathized Ralph, \"Ive been out chasing the fire trucks on a couple of chimney fires and I've slopped through all the mud and slush I'm going to for one day. Gosh! But I'd like to hop over a few clouds in the _Good News_.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000336","text":"The telephone on Tim's desk rang and he turned to answer. He was smiling when he swung back and faced Ralph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000337","text":"Dash off your copy,\" he said. \"Carl Hunter, the manager at the airport, just phoned that the _Good News_ is ready for a test flight. If we cut lunch this noon we'll have time for a short hop. What say?","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000338","text":"Don't ask foolish questions,\" grinned Ralph. He hurried to his typewriter where his fingers were soon beating a tattoo on flying keys as he wrote the story of the fires.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000339","text":"Ralph finished his story, turned it in at the copy desk, and was on his way to rejoin Tim when a deep rumble shook the building.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000340","text":"Earthquake!\" shouted one of the copy boys as he dove under a desk.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000341","text":"The windows rattled in their frames and the entire building shook as the terrific noise continued. Then a great pall of black smoke could be seen mounting skyward. The building ceased its trembling, the copy boy scrambled out from under the desk and the telephones voiced their sharp cries.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000342","text":"From his attitude others in the news room sensed some major disaster.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000343","text":"The managing editor, George Carson, human dynamo of the paper, ran to Tim's desk and leaned close to the receiver.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000344","text":"He could hear the words which were being shouted into the transmitter at the other end of the line.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000345","text":"The managing editor turned to Ralph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000346","text":"Run to the composing room,\" he cried. \"Tell them to stand by for an extra. The storage tanks on the Midwest Oil Company property west of town have caught fire and are exploding.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000347","text":"Ralph waited to hear no more, but ran to the composing room where he gave the managing editor's message to the foreman. Then he hurried back to the editorial office.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000348","text":"Tim was scribbling a bulletin for the extra with one hand while he listened to the first report of the explosion.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000349","text":"Five or six men were missing. They might have been caught in the first blast or perhaps they had escaped and were too excited to report their safety.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000350","text":"The managing editor took the story as fast as Tim could write it, wrote a new banner line for the front page, and rushed the copy to the composing room.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000351","text":"One of the mechanics from the airport,\" said Tim. \"The storage tanks are only a mile and a half from the field and he saw the first one let go. A man from the oil company is at the field now and they are getting the story from him.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000352","text":"Is the _Good News_ in condition to fly?\" asked the managing editor.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000353","text":"Just got word a few minutes ago she was ready to test,\" replied Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000354","text":"Is it safe to go up on a picture assignment for photos of those burning oil tanks?","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000355","text":"If you'll pay for all the paint I scorch off the plane,\" said Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000356","text":"We'll pay for it,\" cried Carson. \"Take Ralph with you and get all the pictures you can. We'll want them for the city final. And whatever you do, don't let your motor cut out when you're over those burning tanks.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000357","text":"If it does you'll have to look for two new reporters,\" chuckled Ralph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000358","text":"Tim turned the telephone over to another reporter and they stopped only long enough to get a camera and make sure that it had a plentiful supply of plates.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000359","text":"The editorial office was in an uproar.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000360","text":"A heavy pall of oily, black smoke blanketed the city and some streets were so dark the street lights had been turned on.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000361","text":"Tim and Ralph ran to the nearby garage where the cars used by _News_ Reporters were stored.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000362","text":"They took the first machine available, a light, speedy roadster.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000363","text":"Tim climbed behind the wheel and they shot out of the garage.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000364","text":"Traffic down town was in a tangled jam that would take an hour to clear for the rumbling explosions from the oil tanks had alarmed the entire city.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000365","text":"Many people, believing that the city was about to fall on their heads, had hurried to their cars in an attempt to flee to the open country.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000366","text":"Now they were just as anxious to return to their homes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000367","text":"By sliding through alleys, Tim managed to get to a fairly clear boulevard that led to the airport. A light breeze had started to clear the smoke from the air and Tim stepped on the accelerator. The indicator on the speedometer climbed steadily--forty, forty-five and fifty miles an hour.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000368","text":"Look out,\" cried Ralph, \"Or we'll be picked up for speeding.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000369","text":"No chance,\" replied Tim. \"All the police are at the fire. We've got to make time if we want good pictures.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000370","text":"Tim and Ralph were supremely happy as they sped toward the airport.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000371","text":"They were going into the clouds again--into the clouds in quest of the news and the pictures.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000372","text":"Barely a year before the _News_ had purchased an airplane and Tim had been assigned the duties of flying reporter.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000373","text":"Ralph had been selected to help and Tim had trained his friend as a flyer.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000374","text":"Together they had uncovered some of the biggest stories of the year for the _News_ and their exploits had become exceedingly popular with the people of Atkinson.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000375","text":"Now they were off on a new adventure and their hearts beat faster as they neared the airport.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000376","text":"To their right great billows of smoke mounted skyward from the burning storage tanks and occasionally tongues of flame could be seen as the fire made some new conquest.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000377","text":"The airport was just beyond the city limits and its administration building and hangars flanked the boulevard. Tim spun the roadster through the gate and stopped beside hanger No. 5.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000378","text":"The broad doors of the hangar had been rolled open and the _Good News_, its nose pointed toward the field, was waiting for them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000379","text":"The metal propeller was turning slowly as the engine idled. The fuselage had been painted a brilliant crimson with the wings a contrast in silver grey.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000380","text":"Carl Hunter, quiet, efficient manager of the field, was waiting for them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000381","text":"How does the new engine sound?\" asked Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000382","text":"Mighty sweet,\" replied Hunter.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000383","text":"I haven't had her up for I knew you would want the first flight.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000384","text":"However, I gave her a thorough test on the blocks and she never missed a stroke.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000385","text":"Boy, you've got some plane with that new 250 horsepower radial motor.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000386","text":"You'll do 200 miles an hour and have plenty of power to spare.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000387","text":"They hastened to the plane where Tim and Ralph made a quick but thorough inspection. The biplane had been overhauled and re-rigged during the winter with a new, more powerful motor. The _Good News_ would be fifty miles an hour faster.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000388","text":"The flying reporters climbed into their cockpits. Ralph, who was to handle the camera, took the forward cockpit and Tim handled the controls in the rear one.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000389","text":"Tim opened the throttle and listened attentively as he ran the motor up and down the scale. There was never a second's hesitation.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000390","text":"Hunter came close and shouted in Tim's ear.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000391","text":"Don't get too close to the fire,\" he cried. \"The heat will raise the dickens with the air and it will be pretty rocky.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000392","text":"Tim nodded and motioned for the blocks to be cleared away.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000393","text":"The _Good News_ rolled easily out of the hangar, flipped its tail saucily at the few mechanics left at the field, and roared over the soggy ground and into the air.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000394","text":"Tim thrilled to the touch of the controls and the _Good News_ answered even to the slightest movement of the stick.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000395","text":"The new motor settled to its work in a manner that warmed Tim's heart. He felt that he had reserve power for any emergency as he swung the biplane around and headed for the burning oil tanks.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000396","text":"Tim put the _Good News_ in a steady climb and they gained altitude rapidly. At 1,200 feet he levelled off and Ralph got busy with the camera.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000397","text":"The oil storage lot, a large tract of level land, was dotted with a dozen large tanks.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000398","text":"Five of the tanks had caught fire and exploded, the force of the explosion knocking off the steel tops.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000399","text":"These tops, like great black pancakes, had been blown clear of the tract.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000400","text":"One of them had hurtled down to crush the roof of the house nearest the fire.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000401","text":"The walls of two of the tanks had given way and Tim and Ralph could see the firemen fighting desperately to stop the spread of the flames.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000402","text":"Safety trenches had been a part of the protective system at the tank farm, but some of them had been weakened by the explosion and the flaming gasoline was finding the vulnerable spots.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000403","text":"Tim swung the _Good News_ over the blazing storage tanks and even 1,200 feet in the air they could feel the heat. The plane danced crazily and Ralph, who had been leaning far out, clutched the side of the plane and shook his fist at Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000404","text":"The flying reporter snapped off the throttle and they glided down on a gentle incline, as the propeller turned slowly.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000405","text":"Got enough pictures?\" yelled Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000406","text":"Three more plates left,\" shouted Ralph. \"Let's go down where I can get some close ups. Make a run for the fire at about four hundred feet; then zoom up just before we get there. That will give us some real pictures.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000407","text":"Also scorch all the new paint off the ship,\" protested Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000408","text":"Carson said he'd pay for a new coat,\" Ralph reminded him and Tim nodded and snapped on the switches again. The motor roared into action and they shot down out of the murky sky.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000409","text":"At four hundred feet Tim pulled back on the stick and the _Good News_ levelled off. They were a mile west of the burning tank farm when he banked sharply and swung back toward the city.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000410","text":"The clouds of smoke, rolling upward, were streaked with vivid flashes of flame. Tim chilled as he thought of the fate that would be theirs if their plane failed to respond to the controls. He forced the thought from his mind and took a fresh grip on the stick.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000411","text":"Ralph glanced back and smiled. Tim motioned to his own safety belt and directed Ralph to strap himself into the plane. No telling what might happen in the next smoky-flame seared seconds.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000412","text":"Tim pushed the _Good News_ into several tight banks while Ralph strapped himself into the plane. Then they were ready for their picture making dash.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000413","text":"Ralph trained his camera and glued his eyes to the sight. It would be a great action picture, awe inspiring in its power, if they could get it.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000414","text":"Tim, one hand on the stick and the other on the throttle, watched his air speed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000415","text":"Half a mile from the burning tanks they were going one hundred and fifty miles an hour.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000416","text":"A quarter of a mile away and their speed had increased to one hundred and seventy-five.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000417","text":"Then there was no more time to check the air speed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000418","text":"They were going fast enough and Tim knew his motor had plenty of reserve power for any emergency.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000419","text":"Ralph, in the forward cockpit, was busy with his camera. Two exposures of the rolling, mass of smoke and flame were made in the split seconds before Tim threw the _Good News_ into a steep zoom.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000420","text":"The towering pillar of smoke was less than five hundred feet ahead of their propeller when Tim put the pressure on the stick. The nose shot skyward and the _Good News_ danced upward along the outer rim of smoke.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000421","text":"Ralph was ready for the final exposure when a terrific explosion and a wave of rag flame and heat tore the heavens asunder. The _Good News_ leaped upward, bucking like a wild horse. Tim, his eyebrows singed and lungs burning from the scorching heat, fought the controls.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000422","text":"Up, up, up pitched the _Good News_, tossing wildly on the edge of the inferno of flame and smoke. The noise of the explosion had deadened their ears and neither Ralph nor Tim could hear the laboring of the motor as Tim gave it full throttle.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000423","text":"The new paint on the wings and fuselage curled and darkened in the heat and for a second Tim thought the gasoline tank might explode.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000424","text":"Then above it all came the sound of a second explosion and the _Good News_ stood up on its tail. Tim was thankful that they had used their safety belts for he was almost thrown from the cockpit.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000425","text":"Out of the smoke hurtled a great piece of steel. Tim heard Ralph scream a warning but he was powerless. The _Good News_ was out of control.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000426","text":"Fascinated by the sight of the great projectile which was approaching them with terrifying speed, Tim lived an eternity. Actually it might have been a second, probably it was less.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000427","text":"The _Good News_, falling tail downward, missed the deadly piece of steel by less than two feet.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000428","text":"They were past one danger only to be confronted with another even more horrible to contemplate than the one they had just escaped. Ralph, his eyes burning in his smoke-blackened face, was looking back at Tim, trusting that the young flyer would be able to pull the _Good News_ out of the tailspin.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000429","text":"With a last despairing effort Tim crashed his fist against the throttle. It leaped ahead a good inch. It had jammed in the emergency and he had not noticed it. More fuel flooded into the laboring cylinders and the motor, its full power unlashed, lifted them almost vertically into the sky.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000430","text":"When they were out of danger and in the cool, clean air, Tim brought the nose of the plane down and they headed for the airport.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000431","text":"The _Good News_ looked to be ready to take first prize at a fire sale. The entire ship was grimy from the heavy oil smoke and the dope on the wings and fuselage was curled and cracked from the terrific heat.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000432","text":"Tim nosed down over the airport and idled his motor as they skimmed to a perfect three point landing and rolled to a stop in front of their hangar.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000433","text":"Carl Hunter ran to their plane.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000434","text":"You crazy news hounds,\" he cried. \"I thought you were goners when those explosions caught you. How did you ever get out alive?","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000435","text":"We'll thank the new motor for saving our necks,\" replied Tim. \"We were in trouble, believe me. The throttle stuck and the engine wasn't getting all the gas. In a moment of desperation I smashed the throttle with my fist and opened it. A second later and we were climbing to safety.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000436","text":"Good thing you made me strap myself in,\" grinned Ralph, \"Or you would have lost your passenger when we took that wild west ride.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000437","text":"We were mighty lucky to get back,\" said Tim. \"Next time we cover a fire on an oil tank farm we'll know enough to stay at a safe distance.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000438","text":"But think of the great action pictures we've got,\" said Ralph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000439","text":"I'm thinking of my own neck right now,\" replied Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000440","text":"When the second explosion came and that piece of steel picked us out for a target I just said good-bye to everything.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000441","text":"While we're passing around the thanks for getting out alive we'll have to include old lady gravity.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000442","text":"The _Good News_ was dropping earthward just fast enough for us to escape.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000443","text":"We'd better get these pictures to the office so they can use them in the final,\" said Ralph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000444","text":"You take the camera and the car and go on,\" said Tim. \"I won't be needed at the office for a while and I want to check over the plane and see if it suffered any serious damage. Tell Carson he'll have to okay an order for another coat of paint.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000445","text":"I'll wait and see how the pictures come out before I tell him,\" chuckled Ralph as he got in the roadster and started for the office.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000446","text":"Tim and Hunter went over the _Good News_ carefully, checking every joint and strut. Then they gave the motor a thorough test. It was sweet and true.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000447","text":"A real plane,\" was the field manager's comment when they had completed their inspection. \"After a test like the one to-day you can count on it carrying you through anything short of a hurricane.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000448","text":"I'm not so sure it wouldn't do that,\" said Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000449","text":"We'd better fill up the gasoline tank,\" he added. \"Never can tell when we may get an assignment that will call for another quick getaway.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000450","text":"They refueled the ship and were rolling it back into the hangar when a car skidded through the gate. The managing editor and Ralph were in the machine and from their haste Tim knew that he would soon be in the clouds again on the trail of another big story.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000451","text":"The managing editor of the _News_ jumped from the car before Ralph brought it to a stop and ran toward Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000452","text":"Can you start on another assignment right away?\" he asked.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000453","text":"Whenever you say, Mr. Carson,\" replied Tim. \"We've just made a complete check and the _Good News_ isn't hurt in the least. She's refueled and ready to go.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000454","text":"Then you're heading for Cedar river valley,\" said the managing editor.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000455","text":"The village of Auburn you took food and medical supplies to last spring when the Cedar was on a rampage is in need of help again.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000456","text":"The river is causing trouble and the worst ice jam in the history of the country is just above the village.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000457","text":"This changeable weather has kept the river thawing and then freezing and thousands of tons of ice are piling up behind the jam.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000458","text":"I want you and Ralph to make a trip there this afternoon, survey the situation, get all the pictures you can, and report to me.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000459","text":"When we know the size of the jam we can plan to get relief to them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000460","text":"We'll be on our way in ten minutes,\" promised Tim. \"The people at Auburn helped me when I was working on the Sky Hawk mystery and I'll be glad of the chance to do another favor for them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000461","text":"In the excitement of this new story,\" said the managing editor, \"I almost forgot to tell you how much I appreciate your fine work in getting the pictures of the fire at the oil tanks.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000462","text":"I've never seen anything like them for action.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000463","text":"They were so good we put out an extra with nothing but pictures on the front page.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000464","text":"Biggest selling extra ever published in Atkinson.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000465","text":"They may prove fairly expensive by the time you pay the cost of a new coat of paint for the _Good News_,\" said Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000466","text":"Hang the cost of the paint,\" exclaimed the managing editor, \"Those pictures were worth $500 to the paper. Why the one showing that piece of steel hurtling up out of the smoke and flame is the best action picture ever taken.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000467","text":"The picture showing that piece of steel coming toward you,\" repeated Carson.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000468","text":"I'll explain,\" said Ralph, and he turned to Tim.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000469","text":"We had a lucky break,\" he continued.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000470","text":"When that explosion caught us I had only one plate left in the camera.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000471","text":"In the excitement I snapped the shutter and it so happened that the camera was aimed to get that steel plate that almost wrote 'finish' for us.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000472","text":"We'll be able to sell that picture all over the country,\" said the managing editor, \"And I'll see that you boys get half of whatever the paper makes on it.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000473","text":"Carl Hunter came out of the administration building to report that the weather in the direction of Cedar Valley was fair.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000474","text":"Better get into some heavier clothes,\" he warned, \"For it will be pretty breezy up there if Tim decides to step on the gas.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000475","text":"Our winter flying outfits are all in town,\" said Ralph. \"Guess we can make it this way.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000476","text":"I've got some spare clothes,\" suggested Hunter. \"Some of them belong to 'Tiny' Lewis but they'll keep you warm at least.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000477","text":"The young reporters laughed at the thought of wearing \"Tiny\" Lewis' flying togs. \"Tiny,\" was the exact opposite from his name. He was as round as a barrel and not much over five feet six in height.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000478","text":"The boys followed Hunter back to the administration building and made their way to the pilots' room. Hunter opened several lockers and finally found the clothes he sought, heavy fleece-lined coveralls especially designed for cold weather flying.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000479","text":"When the boys had donned their ill-fitting clothes they looked like a pair of aerial scare crows for their legs projected awkwardly from the suits, which were far too short for them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000480","text":"Throw a couple of robes over your legs and you'll be all right,\" suggested the field manager.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000481","text":"Not for me,\" grinned Tim. \"Ralph can bundle up all he wants to but I'm not going to have a blanket tangled around the stick just about the time I have to get into action.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000482","text":"When the boys returned to No. 5 hangar the mechanics had the _Good News_ warmed up and on the line.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000483","text":"The managing editor looked at his watch.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000484","text":"Just a few minutes after one-thirty,\" he said, half to himself, half to his star reporters.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000485","text":"Then aloud he said, \"You won't be able to get to Auburn, snap your pictures and get back here in time for the city final.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000486","text":"However, if you get some good shots we'll put out a five o'clock picture extra so step on it all the way.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000487","text":"We'll be back in less than two hours,\" promised Tim. \"Wouldn't be able to do it with the old motor in the ship, but with this new power unit we'll do 180 an hour steady over and back. The trip is about 125 miles each way and with the time it takes for the pictures we'll make it in two hours easy.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000488","text":"Then I'll have the engravers and the composing room stand by for a five o'clock picture extra,\" said the managing editor.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000489","text":"This will be a red-letter day in the history of the _News_--two picture extras in the same day and believe me, boys, that's what the readers want.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000490","text":"Pictures, action, and more pictures.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000491","text":"Ralph lifted his big camera into the front cockpit and settled himself for the trip. He wrapped a heavy robe around his legs for he knew Tim was going to tear loose on the trip to Auburn and even though it was moderately warm on the ground the air at two thousand feet would be chilly.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000492","text":"Tim checked his instruments, waved for the mechanics to get in the clear, and opened his throttle.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000493","text":"The _Good News_ lifted her tail off the muddy field, splattered the water out of half a dozen puddles, and then shot up into her own domain.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000494","text":"The new radial motor, tested in flame and smoke little more than an hour before, leaped to its task and they sped away into the east. Behind them the fire still raged at the oil tanks, but firemen appeared to have checked its spread.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000495","text":"Tim pushed the throttle steadily forward until the air speed indicator registered 175 miles an hour.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000496","text":"At 2,000 feet the ground was a dull, gray checkerboard beneath them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000497","text":"In places there were splotches of dirty snow, a last vestige of winter.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000498","text":"Creeks, silver ribbons winding through the countryside, were running bankfull of water.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000499","text":"Several times they sighted streams in which the outgoing ice had jammed around some bridge or sharp curve.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000500","text":"Behind these jams the stream had spread out until it formed a small lake.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000501","text":"None of them were of major importance but at one bridge half a dozen men were busy trying to dynamite the mass of ice which was threatening the safety of the structure.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000502","text":"As they neared the valley of the mighty Cedar the country became rougher and there were fewer fields for an emergency landing. A plane in trouble in the valley would have small chance of making a safe descent.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000503","text":"They were fifteen miles from Auburn when they caught their first glimpse of the river, a great lake stretching for miles up its valley.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000504","text":"Then they saw the jumbled mass of ice above the village. The towering blocks had jammed at a sharp bend in the river and hundreds of tons of ice, born by the spring freshets, had built a great dam which was impounding the waters of the river.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000505","text":"The bed of the stream below the ice jam carried little more than a trickle of water when compared to the usual volume.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000506","text":"From the position of the jam Tim could see that unless the pressure was relieved soon the water behind the ice, spreading out over the valley, would soon creep around the wings of the jam and sweep down on the village.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000507","text":"The _Good News_ slid down out of the clouds and swung over the scene of the impending disaster.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000508","text":"The village was practically deserted.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000509","text":"Men and women were at the jam, working side by side in what appeared a futile effort to start the thousands of tons of ice moving down stream before their own homes were destroyed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000510","text":"Tim guided the _Good News_ up the valley, over the jam, and on up stream. The jam of ice extended nearly a half mile above the village. The river above that point, running free, was piling more ice on the jam, adding to the pressure which hourly threatened to let go and sweep everything before it.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000511","text":"Ralph, leaning far over the side of the plane, was busy with his camera. He motioned for Tim to return to the village. There they took pictures of the practically deserted town and Tim dropped low enough for Ralph to get some good flashes of the men and women working along the edge of the ice jam.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000512","text":"Just a year before the villagers had helped Tim when he was on the trail of the Sky Hawk and he felt that he owed them a real debt.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000513","text":"They gazed upward as the plane sped over them but they did not recognize the scorched, blackened plane as the _Good News_. Tim and Ralph waved eagerly, but there was no reply. The villagers were weighted down with despair.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000514","text":"Ralph indicated that he had used the last of the plates in the camera and Tim swung the _Good News_ into the west. He headed back for Atkinson at 180 miles an hour, the motor singing as they shot through the greying sky.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000515","text":"The clouds were dropping on them and by the time they were half way to Atkinson they had a ceiling of less than six hundred feet.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000516","text":"Tim tried to rise above the clouds, but they were massed solidly.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000517","text":"He climbed to the five thousand foot level only to find himself lost in swirling vapor and with the air growing colder every minute.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000518","text":"Ice started to form on the wings of the _Good News_ and Tim realized the danger. The plane was harder to handle, slower to answer the controls.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000519","text":"Ralph sensed the danger of the higher altitude and motioned for Tim to dive, but the flying reporter shook his head. He was too experienced an airman for a power dive when ice was gathering on his ship.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000520","text":"To have nosed the ship down at 180 miles an hour might be fatal for both of them.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000521","text":"With the ceiling probably down to nothing they would flash out of the clouds at high speed with only a few hundred feet of clearance.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000522","text":"Normally they could get away with it but with the wings weighted down with ice one of them might snap off when he pulled back on the stick.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"The Mumonkan — Yamada trans. (1903)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000523","text":"There are two editions of this ebook in the Project Gutenberg collection. Various characteristics of each ebook are listed to aid in selecting the preferred file.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000524","text":"Click on any of the filenumbers below to quickly view each ebook.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000525","text":"27 1874, First Edition; illustrated.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000526","text":"107 1895, Second Edition, extensively revised by Thomas Hardy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000527","text":"Description of Farmer Oak—An Incident Chapter II.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000528","text":"Night—The Flock—An Interior—Another Interior Chapter III.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000529","text":"A Girl on Horseback—Conversation Chapter IV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000530","text":"Gabriel’s Resolve—The Visit—The Mistake Chapter V.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000531","text":"Departure of Bathsheba—A Pastoral Tragedy Chapter VI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000532","text":"The Fair—The Journey—The Fire Chapter VII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000533","text":"Recognition—A Timid Girl Chapter VIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000534","text":"The Malthouse—The Chat—News Chapter IX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000535","text":"The Homestead—A Visitor—Half-Confidences Chapter X.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000536","text":"Outside the Barracks—Snow—A Meeting Chapter XII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000537","text":"Farmers—A Rule—An Exception Chapter XIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000538","text":"Sortes Sanctorum—The Valentine Chapter XIV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000539","text":"Effect of the Letter—Sunrise Chapter XV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000540","text":"A Morning Meeting—The Letter Again Chapter XVI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000541","text":"All Saints’ and All Souls’ Chapter XVII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000542","text":"In the Market-Place Chapter XVIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000543","text":"Boldwood in Meditation—Regret Chapter XIX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000544","text":"The Sheep-Washing—The Offer Chapter XX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000545","text":"Perplexity—Grinding the Shears—A Quarrel Chapter XXI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000546","text":"Troubles in the Fold—A Message Chapter XXII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000547","text":"The Great Barn and the Sheep-Shearers Chapter XXIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000548","text":"Eventide—A Second Declaration Chapter XXIV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000549","text":"The Same Night—The Fir Plantation Chapter XXV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000550","text":"The New Acquaintance Described Chapter XXVI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000551","text":"Scene on the Verge of the Hay-Mead Chapter XXVII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000552","text":"Hiving the Bees Chapter XXVIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000553","text":"The Hollow Amid the Ferns Chapter XXIX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000554","text":"Particulars of a Twilight Walk Chapter XXX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000555","text":"Hot Cheeks and Tearful Eyes Chapter XXXI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000556","text":"Night—Horses Tramping Chapter XXXIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000557","text":"In the Sun—A Harbinger Chapter XXXIV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000558","text":"Home Again—A Trickster Chapter XXXV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000559","text":"At an Upper Window Chapter XXXVI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000560","text":"Wealth in Jeopardy—The Revel Chapter XXXVII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000561","text":"The Storm—The Two Together Chapter XXXVIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000562","text":"Rain—One Solitary Meets Another Chapter XXXIX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000563","text":"On Casterbridge Highway Chapter XLI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000564","text":"Suspicion—Fanny Is Sent For Chapter XLII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000565","text":"Joseph and His Burden—Buck’s Head Chapter XLIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000566","text":"Under a Tree—Reaction Chapter XLV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000567","text":"Troy’s Romanticism Chapter XLVI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000568","text":"The Gurgoyle: Its Doings Chapter XLVII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000569","text":"Adventures by the Shore Chapter XLVIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000570","text":"Doubts Arise—Doubts Linger Chapter XLIX.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000571","text":"Oak’s Advancement—A Great Hope Chapter L.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000572","text":"The Sheep Fair—Troy Touches His Wife’s Hand Chapter LI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000573","text":"Bathsheba Talks with Her Outrider Chapter LII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000574","text":"Converging Courses Chapter LIII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000575","text":"Concurritur—Horæ Momento Chapter LIV.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000576","text":"The March Following—“Bathsheba Boldwood” Chapter LVI.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000577","text":"Beauty in Loneliness—After All Chapter LVII.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000578","text":"A Foggy Night and Morning—Conclusion","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000579","text":"The series of novels I projected being mainly of the kind called local, they seemed to require a territorial definition of some sort to lend unity to their scene.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000580","text":"Finding that the area of a single county did not afford a canvas large enough for this purpose, and that there were objections to an invented name, I disinterred the old one.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000581","text":"I did not anticipate that this application of the word to a modern use would extend outside the chapters of my own chronicles.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000582","text":"But the name was soon taken up elsewhere as a local designation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000583","text":"But I ask all good and gentle readers to be so kind as to forget this, and to refuse steadfastly to believe that there are any inhabitants of a Victorian Wessex outside the pages of this and the companion volumes in which they were first discovered.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000584","text":"The church remains, by great good fortune, unrestored and intact, and a few of the old houses; but the ancient malt-house, which was formerly so characteristic of the parish, has been pulled down these twenty years; also most of the thatched and dormered cottages that were once lifeholds.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000585","text":"The game of prisoner’s base, which not so long ago seemed to enjoy a perennial vitality in front of the worn-out stocks, may, so far as I can say, be entirely unknown to the rising generation of schoolboys there.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000586","text":"For these the indispensable conditions of existence are attachment to the soil of one particular spot by generation after generation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000587","text":"CHAPTER I Description of Farmer Oak—An Incident","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000588","text":"When Farmer Oak smiled, the corners of his mouth spread till they were within an unimportant distance of his ears, his eyes were reduced to chinks, and diverging wrinkles appeared round them, extending upon his countenance like the rays in a rudimentary sketch of the rising sun.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000589","text":"His Christian name was Gabriel, and on working days he was a young man of sound judgment, easy motions, proper dress, and general good character.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000590","text":"Or, to state his character as it stood in the scale of public opinion, when his friends and critics were in tantrums, he was considered rather a bad man; when they were pleased, he was rather a good man; when they were neither, he was a man whose moral colour was a kind of pepper-and-salt mixture.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000591","text":"Since he lived six times as many working-days as Sundays, Oak’s appearance in his old clothes was most peculiarly his own—the mental picture formed by his neighbours in imagining him being always dressed in that way.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000592","text":"He wore a low-crowned felt hat, spread out at the base by tight jamming upon the head for security in high winds, and a coat like Dr.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000593","text":"Oak carried about him, by way of watch, what may be called a small silver clock; in other words, it was a watch as to shape and intention, and a small clock as to size.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000594","text":"This instrument being several years older than Oak’s grandfather, had the peculiarity of going either too fast or not at all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000595","text":"The smaller of its hands, too, occasionally slipped round on the pivot, and thus, though the minutes were told with precision, nobody could be quite certain of the hour they belonged to.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000596","text":"But some thoughtful persons, who had seen him walking across one of his fields on a certain December morning—sunny and exceedingly mild—might have regarded Gabriel Oak in other aspects than these.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000597","text":"In his face one might notice that many of the hues and curves of youth had tarried on to manhood: there even remained in his remoter crannies some relics of the boy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000598","text":"His height and breadth would have been sufficient to make his presence imposing, had they been exhibited with due consideration.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000599","text":"But there is a way some men have, rural and urban alike, for which the mind is more responsible than flesh and sinew: it is a way of curtailing their dimensions by their manner of showing them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000600","text":"And from a quiet modesty that would have become a vestal, which seemed continually to impress upon him that he had no great claim on the world’s room, Oak walked unassumingly and with a faintly perceptible bend, yet distinct from a bowing of the shoulders.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000601","text":"This may be said to be a defect in an individual if he depends for his valuation more upon his appearance than upon his capacity to wear well, which Oak did not.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000602","text":"He had just reached the time of life at which “young” is ceasing to be the prefix of “man” in speaking of one.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000603","text":"In short, he was twenty-eight, and a bachelor.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000604","text":"The field he was in this morning sloped to a ridge called Norcombe Hill.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000605","text":"Through a spur of this hill ran the highway between Emminster and Chalk-Newton.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000606","text":"Casually glancing over the hedge, Oak saw coming down the incline before him an ornamental spring waggon, painted yellow and gaily marked, drawn by two horses, a waggoner walking alongside bearing a whip perpendicularly.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000607","text":"The waggon was laden with household goods and window plants, and on the apex of the whole sat a woman, young and attractive.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000608","text":"Gabriel had not beheld the sight for more than half a minute, when the vehicle was brought to a standstill just beneath his eyes.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000609","text":"“The tailboard of the waggon is gone, Miss,” said the waggoner.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000610","text":"“Then I heard it fall,” said the girl, in a soft, though not particularly low voice. “I heard a noise I could not account for when we were coming up the hill.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000611","text":"The sensible horses stood—perfectly still, and the waggoner’s steps sank fainter and fainter in the distance.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000612","text":"The girl on the summit of the load sat motionless, surrounded by tables and chairs with their legs upwards, backed by an oak settle, and ornamented in front by pots of geraniums, myrtles, and cactuses, together with a caged canary—all probably from the windows of the house just vacated.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000613","text":"There was also a cat in a willow basket, from the partly-opened lid of which she gazed with half-closed eyes, and affectionately surveyed the small birds around.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000614","text":"The handsome girl waited for some time idly in her place, and the only sound heard in the stillness was the hopping of the canary up and down the perches of its prison.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000615","text":"Then she looked attentively downwards.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000616","text":"It was not at the bird, nor at the cat; it was at an oblong package tied in paper, and lying between them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000617","text":"She turned her head to learn if the waggoner were coming.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000618","text":"He was not yet in sight; and her eyes crept back to the package, her thoughts seeming to run upon what was inside it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000619","text":"At length she drew the article into her lap, and untied the paper covering; a small swing looking-glass was disclosed, in which she proceeded to survey herself attentively.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000620","text":"She parted her lips and smiled.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000621","text":"It was a fine morning, and the sun lighted up to a scarlet glow the crimson jacket she wore, and painted a soft lustre upon her bright face and dark hair.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000622","text":"The myrtles, geraniums, and cactuses packed around her were fresh and green, and at such a leafless season they invested the whole concern of horses, waggon, furniture, and girl with a peculiar vernal charm.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000623","text":"What possessed her to indulge in such a performance in the sight of the sparrows, blackbirds, and unperceived farmer who were alone its spectators,—whether the smile began as a factitious one, to test her capacity in that art,—nobody knows; it ended certainly in a real smile.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000624","text":"She blushed at herself, and seeing her reflection blush, blushed the more.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000625","text":"The change from the customary spot and necessary occasion of such an act—from the dressing hour in a bedroom to a time of travelling out of doors—lent to the idle deed a novelty it did not intrinsically possess.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000626","text":"The picture was a delicate one.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000627","text":"Woman’s prescriptive infirmity had stalked into the sunlight, which had clothed it in the freshness of an originality.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000628","text":"A cynical inference was irresistible by Gabriel Oak as he regarded the scene, generous though he fain would have been.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000629","text":"There was no necessity whatever for her looking in the glass.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000630","text":"She did not adjust her hat, or pat her hair, or press a dimple into shape, or do one thing to signify that any such intention had been her motive in taking up the glass.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000631","text":"She simply observed herself as a fair product of Nature in the feminine kind, her thoughts seeming to glide into far-off though likely dramas in which men would play a part—vistas of probable triumphs—the smiles being of a phase suggesting that hearts were imagined as lost and won.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000632","text":"Still, this was but conjecture, and the whole series of actions was so idly put forth as to make it rash to assert that intention had any part in them at all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000633","text":"The waggoner’s steps were heard returning. She put the glass in the paper, and the whole again into its place.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000634","text":"When the waggon had passed on, Gabriel withdrew from his point of espial, and descending into the road, followed the vehicle to the turnpike-gate some way beyond the bottom of the hill, where the object of his contemplation now halted for the payment of toll.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000635","text":"About twenty steps still remained between him and the gate, when he heard a dispute.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000636","text":"It was a difference concerning twopence between the persons with the waggon and the man at the toll-bar.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000637","text":"“Mis’ess’s niece is upon the top of the things, and she says that’s enough that I’ve offered ye, you great miser, and she won’t pay any more.” These were the waggoner’s words.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000638","text":"“Very well; then mis’ess’s niece can’t pass,” said the turnpike-keeper, closing the gate.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000639","text":"Oak looked from one to the other of the disputants, and fell into a reverie.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000640","text":"There was something in the tone of twopence remarkably insignificant.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000641","text":"Gabriel’s features adhered throughout their form so exactly to the middle line between the beauty of St.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000642","text":"John and the ugliness of Judas Iscariot, as represented in a window of the church he attended, that not a single lineament could be selected and called worthy either of distinction or notoriety.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000643","text":"The red-jacketed and dark-haired maiden seemed to think so too, for she carelessly glanced over him, and told her man to drive on.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000644","text":"She might have looked her thanks to Gabriel on a minute scale, but she did not speak them; more probably she felt none, for in gaining her a passage he had lost her her point, and we know how women take a favour of that kind.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000645","text":"The gatekeeper surveyed the retreating vehicle. “That’s a handsome maid,” he said to Oak.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000646","text":"“But she has her faults,” said Gabriel.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000647","text":"“And the greatest of them is—well, what it is always.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000648","text":"“Beating people down? ay, ’tis so.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000649","text":"Gabriel, perhaps a little piqued by the comely traveller’s indifference, glanced back to where he had witnessed her performance over the hedge, and said, “Vanity.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000650","text":"CHAPTER II NIGHT—THE FLOCK—AN INTERIOR—ANOTHER INTERIOR","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000651","text":"It was nearly midnight on the eve of St. Thomas’s, the shortest day in the year. A desolating wind wandered from the north over the hill whereon Oak had watched the yellow waggon and its occupant in the sunshine of a few days earlier.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000652","text":"Norcombe Hill—not far from lonely Toller-Down—was one of the spots which suggest to a passer-by that he is in the presence of a shape approaching the indestructible as nearly as any to be found on earth.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000653","text":"It was a featureless convexity of chalk and soil—an ordinary specimen of those smoothly-outlined protuberances of the globe which may remain undisturbed on some great day of confusion, when far grander heights and dizzy granite precipices topple down.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000654","text":"The hill was covered on its northern side by an ancient and decaying plantation of beeches, whose upper verge formed a line over the crest, fringing its arched curve against the sky, like a mane.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000655","text":"To-night these trees sheltered the southern slope from the keenest blasts, which smote the wood and floundered through it with a sound as of grumbling, or gushed over its crowning boughs in a weakened moan.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000656","text":"The dry leaves in the ditch simmered and boiled in the same breezes, a tongue of air occasionally ferreting out a few, and sending them spinning across the grass.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000657","text":"A group or two of the latest in date amongst the dead multitude had remained till this very mid-winter time on the twigs which bore them and in falling rattled against the trunks with smart taps.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000658","text":"Between this half-wooded half-naked hill, and the vague still horizon that its summit indistinctly commanded, was a mysterious sheet of fathomless shade—the sounds from which suggested that what it concealed bore some reduced resemblance to features here.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000659","text":"The thin grasses, more or less coating the hill, were touched by the wind in breezes of differing powers, and almost of differing natures—one rubbing the blades heavily, another raking them piercingly, another brushing them like a soft broom.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000660","text":"The sky was clear—remarkably clear—and the twinkling of all the stars seemed to be but throbs of one body, timed by a common pulse.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000661","text":"The North Star was directly in the wind’s eye, and since evening the Bear had swung round it outwardly to the east, till he was now at a right angle with the meridian.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000662","text":"A difference of colour in the stars—oftener read of than seen in England—was really perceptible here.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000663","text":"The sovereign brilliancy of Sirius pierced the eye with a steely glitter, the star called Capella was yellow, Aldebaran and Betelgueux shone with a fiery red.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000664","text":"To persons standing alone on a hill during a clear midnight such as this, the roll of the world eastward is almost a palpable movement.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000665","text":"After such a nocturnal reconnoitre it is hard to get back to earth, and to believe that the consciousness of such majestic speeding is derived from a tiny human frame.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000666","text":"Suddenly an unexpected series of sounds began to be heard in this place up against the sky. They had a clearness which was to be found nowhere in the wind, and a sequence which was to be found nowhere in nature. They were the notes of Farmer Oak’s flute.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000667","text":"The tune was not floating unhindered into the open air: it seemed muffled in some way, and was altogether too curtailed in power to spread high or wide.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000668","text":"It came from the direction of a small dark object under the plantation hedge—a shepherd’s hut—now presenting an outline to which an uninitiated person might have been puzzled to attach either meaning or use.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000669","text":"The hut stood on little wheels, which raised its floor about a foot from the ground.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000670","text":"Such shepherds’ huts are dragged into the fields when the lambing season comes on, to shelter the shepherd in his enforced nightly attendance.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000671","text":"It was only latterly that people had begun to call Gabriel “Farmer” Oak.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000672","text":"During the twelvemonth preceding this time he had been enabled by sustained efforts of industry and chronic good spirits to lease the small sheep-farm of which Norcombe Hill was a portion, and stock it with two hundred sheep.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000673","text":"Previously he had been a bailiff for a short time, and earlier still a shepherd only, having from his childhood assisted his father in tending the flocks of large proprietors, till old Gabriel sank to rest.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000674","text":"This venture, unaided and alone, into the paths of farming as master and not as man, with an advance of sheep not yet paid for, was a critical juncture with Gabriel Oak, and he recognised his position clearly.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000675","text":"The first movement in his new progress was the lambing of his ewes, and sheep having been his speciality from his youth, he wisely refrained from deputing the task of tending them at this season to a hireling or a novice.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000676","text":"The wind continued to beat about the corners of the hut, but the flute-playing ceased.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000677","text":"A rectangular space of light appeared in the side of the hut, and in the opening the outline of Farmer Oak’s figure.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000678","text":"He carried a lantern in his hand, and closing the door behind him, came forward and busied himself about this nook of the field for nearly twenty minutes, the lantern light appearing and disappearing here and there, and brightening him or darkening him as he stood before or behind it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000679","text":"Oak’s motions, though they had a quiet energy, were slow, and their deliberateness accorded well with his occupation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000680","text":"Fitness being the basis of beauty, nobody could have denied that his steady swings and turns in and about the flock had elements of grace.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000681","text":"Yet, although if occasion demanded he could do or think a thing with as mercurial a dash as can the men of towns who are more to the manner born, his special power, morally, physically, and mentally, was static, owing little or nothing to momentum as a rule.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000682","text":"A close examination of the ground hereabout, even by the wan starlight only, revealed how a portion of what would have been casually called a wild slope had been appropriated by Farmer Oak for his great purpose this winter.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000683","text":"Detached hurdles thatched with straw were stuck into the ground at various scattered points, amid and under which the whitish forms of his meek ewes moved and rustled.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000684","text":"The ring of the sheep-bell, which had been silent during his absence, recommenced, in tones that had more mellowness than clearness, owing to an increasing growth of surrounding wool.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000685","text":"This continued till Oak withdrew again from the flock.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000686","text":"He returned to the hut, bringing in his arms a new-born lamb, consisting of four legs large enough for a full-grown sheep, united by a seemingly inconsiderable membrane about half the substance of the legs collectively, which constituted the animal’s entire body just at present.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000687","text":"The little speck of life he placed on a wisp of hay before the small stove, where a can of milk was simmering.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000688","text":"Oak extinguished the lantern by blowing into it and then pinching the snuff, the cot being lighted by a candle suspended by a twisted wire.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000689","text":"A rather hard couch, formed of a few corn sacks thrown carelessly down, covered half the floor of this little habitation, and here the young man stretched himself along, loosened his woollen cravat, and closed his eyes.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000690","text":"In about the time a person unaccustomed to bodily labour would have decided upon which side to lie, Farmer Oak was asleep.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000691","text":"The inside of the hut, as it now presented itself, was cosy and alluring, and the scarlet handful of fire in addition to the candle, reflecting its own genial colour upon whatever it could reach, flung associations of enjoyment even over utensils and tools.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000692","text":"In the corner stood the sheep-crook, and along a shelf at one side were ranged bottles and canisters of the simple preparations pertaining to ovine surgery and physic; spirits of wine, turpentine, tar, magnesia, ginger, and castor-oil being the chief.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000693","text":"On a triangular shelf across the corner stood bread, bacon, cheese, and a cup for ale or cider, which was supplied from a flagon beneath.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000694","text":"Beside the provisions lay the flute, whose notes had lately been called forth by the lonely watcher to beguile a tedious hour.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000695","text":"The house was ventilated by two round holes, like the lights of a ship’s cabin, with wood slides.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000696","text":"The lamb, revived by the warmth, began to bleat, and the sound entered Gabriel’s ears and brain with an instant meaning, as expected sounds will.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000697","text":"Passing from the profoundest sleep to the most alert wakefulness with the same ease that had accompanied the reverse operation, he looked at his watch, found that the hour-hand had shifted again, put on his hat, took the lamb in his arms, and carried it into the darkness.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000698","text":"After placing the little creature with its mother, he stood and carefully examined the sky, to ascertain the time of night from the altitudes of the stars.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000699","text":"The Dog-star and Aldebaran, pointing to the restless Pleiades, were half-way up the Southern sky, and between them hung Orion, which gorgeous constellation never burnt more vividly than now, as it soared forth above the rim of the landscape.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000700","text":"Being a man not without a frequent consciousness that there was some charm in this life he led, he stood still after looking at the sky as a useful instrument, and regarded it in an appreciative spirit, as a work of art superlatively beautiful.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000701","text":"For a moment he seemed impressed with the speaking loneliness of the scene, or rather with the complete abstraction from all its compass of the sights and sounds of man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000702","text":"Human shapes, interferences, troubles, and joys were all as if they were not, and there seemed to be on the shaded hemisphere of the globe no sentient being save himself; he could fancy them all gone round to the sunny side.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000703","text":"Occupied thus, with eyes stretched afar, Oak gradually perceived that what he had previously taken to be a star low down behind the outskirts of the plantation was in reality no such thing. It was an artificial light, almost close at hand.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000704","text":"Farmer Oak went towards the plantation and pushed through its lower boughs to the windy side.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000705","text":"A dim mass under the slope reminded him that a shed occupied a place here, the site being a cutting into the slope of the hill, so that at its back part the roof was almost level with the ground.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000706","text":"In front it was formed of board nailed to posts and covered with tar as a preservative.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000707","text":"Through crevices in the roof and side spread streaks and dots of light, a combination of which made the radiance that had attracted him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000708","text":"Oak stepped up behind, where, leaning down upon the roof and putting his eye close to a hole, he could see into the interior clearly.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000709","text":"The place contained two women and two cows.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000710","text":"By the side of the latter a steaming bran-mash stood in a bucket.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000711","text":"One of the women was past middle age.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000712","text":"Her companion was apparently young and graceful; he could form no decided opinion upon her looks, her position being almost beneath his eye, so that he saw her in a bird’s-eye view, as Milton’s Satan first saw Paradise.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000713","text":"She wore no bonnet or hat, but had enveloped herself in a large cloak, which was carelessly flung over her head as a covering.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000714","text":"“There, now we’ll go home,” said the elder of the two, resting her knuckles upon her hips, and looking at their goings-on as a whole. “I do hope Daisy will fetch round again now. I have never been more frightened in my life, but I don’t mind breaking my rest if she recovers.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000715","text":"The young woman, whose eyelids were apparently inclined to fall together on the smallest provocation of silence, yawned without parting her lips to any inconvenient extent, whereupon Gabriel caught the infection and slightly yawned in sympathy.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000716","text":"“I wish we were rich enough to pay a man to do these things,” she said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000717","text":"“As we are not, we must do them ourselves,” said the other; “for you must help me if you stay.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000718","text":"“Well, my hat is gone, however,” continued the younger. “It went over the hedge, I think. The idea of such a slight wind catching it.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000719","text":"The cow standing erect was of the Devon breed, and was encased in a tight warm hide of rich Indian red, as absolutely uniform from eyes to tail as if the animal had been dipped in a dye of that colour, her long back being mathematically level.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000720","text":"The other was spotted, grey and white.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000721","text":"Between the sheep and the cows Lucina had been busy on Norcombe Hill lately.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000722","text":"“I think we had better send for some oatmeal,” said the elder woman; “there’s no more bran.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000723","text":"“Yes, aunt; and I’ll ride over for it as soon as it is light.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000724","text":"“I can ride on the other: trust me.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000725","text":"Oak, upon hearing these remarks, became more curious to observe her features, but this prospect being denied him by the hooding effect of the cloak, and by his aërial position, he felt himself drawing upon his fancy for their details.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000726","text":"In making even horizontal and clear inspections we colour and mould according to the wants within us whatever our eyes bring in.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000727","text":"Had Gabriel been able from the first to get a distinct view of her countenance, his estimate of it as very handsome or slightly so would have been as his soul required a divinity at the moment or was ready supplied with one.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000728","text":"Having for some time known the want of a satisfactory form to fill an increasing void within him, his position moreover affording the widest scope for his fancy, he painted her a beauty.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000729","text":"By one of those whimsical coincidences in which Nature, like a busy mother, seems to spare a moment from her unremitting labours to turn and make her children smile, the girl now dropped the cloak, and forth tumbled ropes of black hair over a red jacket.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000730","text":"Oak knew her instantly as the heroine of the yellow waggon, myrtles, and looking-glass: prosily, as the woman who owed him twopence.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000731","text":"They placed the calf beside its mother again, took up the lantern, and went out, the light sinking down the hill till it was no more than a nebula. Gabriel Oak returned to his flock.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000732","text":"CHAPTER III A GIRL ON HORSEBACK—CONVERSATION","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000733","text":"The sluggish day began to break.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000734","text":"Even its position terrestrially is one of the elements of a new interest, and for no particular reason save that the incident of the night had occurred there Oak went again into the plantation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000735","text":"Lingering and musing here, he heard the steps of a horse at the foot of the hill, and soon there appeared in view an auburn pony with a girl on its back, ascending by the path leading past the cattle-shed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000736","text":"She was the young woman of the night before.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000737","text":"Gabriel instantly thought of the hat she had mentioned as having lost in the wind; possibly she had come to look for it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000738","text":"He hastily scanned the ditch and after walking about ten yards along it found the hat among the leaves.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000739","text":"Gabriel took it in his hand and returned to his hut.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000740","text":"Here he ensconced himself, and peeped through the loophole in the direction of the rider’s approach.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000741","text":"She came up and looked around—then on the other side of the hedge.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000742","text":"Gabriel was about to advance and restore the missing article when an unexpected performance induced him to suspend the action for the present.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000743","text":"The path, after passing the cowshed, bisected the plantation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000744","text":"It was not a bridle-path—merely a pedestrian’s track, and the boughs spread horizontally at a height not greater than seven feet above the ground, which made it impossible to ride erect beneath them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000745","text":"The girl, who wore no riding-habit, looked around for a moment, as if to assure herself that all humanity was out of view, then dexterously dropped backwards flat upon the pony’s back, her head over its tail, her feet against its shoulders, and her eyes to the sky.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000746","text":"The rapidity of her glide into this position was that of a kingfisher—its noiselessness that of a hawk.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000747","text":"Gabriel’s eyes had scarcely been able to follow her.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000748","text":"The tall lank pony seemed used to such doings, and ambled along unconcerned.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000749","text":"Thus she passed under the level boughs.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000750","text":"The performer seemed quite at home anywhere between a horse’s head and its tail, and the necessity for this abnormal attitude having ceased with the passage of the plantation, she began to adopt another, even more obviously convenient than the first.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000751","text":"She had no side-saddle, and it was very apparent that a firm seat upon the smooth leather beneath her was unattainable sideways.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000752","text":"Springing to her accustomed perpendicular like a bowed sapling, and satisfying herself that nobody was in sight, she seated herself in the manner demanded by the saddle, though hardly expected of the woman, and trotted off in the direction of Tewnell Mill.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000753","text":"Oak was amused, perhaps a little astonished, and hanging up the hat in his hut, went again among his ewes.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000754","text":"An hour passed, the girl returned, properly seated now, with a bag of bran in front of her.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000755","text":"On nearing the cattle-shed she was met by a boy bringing a milking-pail, who held the reins of the pony whilst she slid off.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000756","text":"The boy led away the horse, leaving the pail with the young woman.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000757","text":"Soon soft spirts alternating with loud spirts came in regular succession from within the shed, the obvious sounds of a person milking a cow. Gabriel took the lost hat in his hand, and waited beside the path she would follow in leaving the hill.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000758","text":"She came, the pail in one hand, hanging against her knee.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000759","text":"The left arm was extended as a balance, enough of it being shown bare to make Oak wish that the event had happened in the summer, when the whole would have been revealed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000760","text":"There was a bright air and manner about her now, by which she seemed to imply that the desirability of her existence could not be questioned; and this rather saucy assumption failed in being offensive because a beholder felt it to be, upon the whole, true.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000761","text":"Like exceptional emphasis in the tone of a genius, that which would have made mediocrity ridiculous was an addition to recognised power.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000762","text":"It was with some surprise that she saw Gabriel’s face rising like the moon behind the hedge.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000763","text":"The adjustment of the farmer’s hazy conceptions of her charms to the portrait of herself she now presented him with was less a diminution than a difference.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000764","text":"The starting-point selected by the judgment was her height.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000765","text":"She seemed tall, but the pail was a small one, and the hedge diminutive; hence, making allowance for error by comparison with these, she could have been not above the height to be chosen by women as best.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000766","text":"All features of consequence were severe and regular.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000767","text":"Without throwing a Nymphean tissue over a milkmaid, let it be said that here criticism checked itself as out of place, and looked at her proportions with a long consciousness of pleasure.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000768","text":"From the contours of her figure in its upper part, she must have had a beautiful neck and shoulders; but since her infancy nobody had ever seen them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000769","text":"Had she been put into a low dress she would have run and thrust her head into a bush.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000770","text":"Yet she was not a shy girl by any means; it was merely her instinct to draw the line dividing the seen from the unseen higher than they do it in towns.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000771","text":"That the girl’s thoughts hovered about her face and form as soon as she caught Oak’s eyes conning the same page was natural, and almost certain.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000772","text":"The self-consciousness shown would have been vanity if a little more pronounced, dignity if a little less.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000773","text":"Rays of male vision seem to have a tickling effect upon virgin faces in rural districts; she brushed hers with her hand, as if Gabriel had been irritating its pink surface by actual touch, and the free air of her previous movements was reduced at the same time to a chastened phase of itself.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000774","text":"Yet it was the man who blushed, the maid not at all.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000775","text":"“It is mine,” said she, and, from a sense of proportion, kept down to a small smile an inclination to laugh distinctly: “it flew away last night.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000776","text":"“Well—it was.” She was surprised. “How did you know?” she said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000777","text":"“You are Farmer Oak, are you not?”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000778","text":"“That or thereabouts. I’m lately come to this place.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000779","text":"“A large farm?” she inquired, casting her eyes round, and swinging back her hair, which was black in the shaded hollows of its mass; but it being now an hour past sunrise the rays touched its prominent curves with a colour of their own.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000780","text":"“No; not large. About a hundred.” (In speaking of farms the word “acres” is omitted by the natives, by analogy to such old expressions as “a stag of ten.”)","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000781","text":"“I wanted my hat this morning,” she went on. “I had to ride to Tewnell Mill.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000782","text":"“Where?” she inquired, a misgiving bringing every muscle of her lineaments and frame to a standstill.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000783","text":"“Here—going through the plantation, and all down the hill,” said Farmer Oak, with an aspect excessively knowing with regard to some matter in his mind, as he gazed at a remote point in the direction named, and then turned back to meet his colloquist’s eyes.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000784","text":"A perception caused him to withdraw his own eyes from hers as suddenly as if he had been caught in a theft.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000785","text":"Recollection of the strange antics she had indulged in when passing through the trees was succeeded in the girl by a nettled palpitation, and that by a hot face.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000786","text":"It was a time to see a woman redden who was not given to reddening as a rule; not a point in the milkmaid but was of the deepest rose-colour.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000787","text":"From the Maiden’s Blush, through all varieties of the Provence down to the Crimson Tuscany, the countenance of Oak’s acquaintance quickly graduated; whereupon he, in considerateness, turned away his head.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000788","text":"The sympathetic man still looked the other way, and wondered when she would recover coolness sufficient to justify him in facing her again. He heard what seemed to be the flitting of a dead leaf upon the breeze, and looked. She had gone away.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000789","text":"With an air between that of Tragedy and Comedy Gabriel returned to his work.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000790","text":"Five mornings and evenings passed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000791","text":"The young woman came regularly to milk the healthy cow or to attend to the sick one, but never allowed her vision to stray in the direction of Oak’s person.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000792","text":"His want of tact had deeply offended her—not by seeing what he could not help, but by letting her know that he had seen it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000793","text":"For, as without law there is no sin, without eyes there is no indecorum; and she appeared to feel that Gabriel’s espial had made her an indecorous woman without her own connivance.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000794","text":"It was food for great regret with him; it was also a _contretemps_ which touched into life a latent heat he had experienced in that direction.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000795","text":"The acquaintanceship might, however, have ended in a slow forgetting, but for an incident which occurred at the end of the same week.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000796","text":"One afternoon it began to freeze, and the frost increased with evening, which drew on like a stealthy tightening of bonds.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000797","text":"It was a time when in cottages the breath of the sleepers freezes to the sheets; when round the drawing-room fire of a thick-walled mansion the sitters’ backs are cold, even whilst their faces are all aglow.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000798","text":"Many a small bird went to bed supperless that night among the bare boughs.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000799","text":"As the milking-hour drew near, Oak kept his usual watch upon the cowshed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000800","text":"At last he felt cold, and shaking an extra quantity of bedding round the yearling ewes he entered the hut and heaped more fuel upon the stove.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000801","text":"The wind came in at the bottom of the door, and to prevent it Oak laid a sack there and wheeled the cot round a little more to the south.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000802","text":"Then the wind spouted in at a ventilating hole—of which there was one on each side of the hut.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000803","text":"Gabriel had always known that when the fire was lighted and the door closed one of these must be kept open—that chosen being always on the side away from the wind.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000804","text":"Closing the slide to windward, he turned to open the other; on second thoughts the farmer considered that he would first sit down leaving both closed for a minute or two, till the temperature of the hut was a little raised.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000805","text":"His head began to ache in an unwonted manner, and, fancying himself weary by reason of the broken rests of the preceding nights, Oak decided to get up, open the slide, and then allow himself to fall asleep. He fell asleep, however, without having performed the necessary preliminary.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000806","text":"How long he remained unconscious Gabriel never knew. During the first stages of his return to perception peculiar deeds seemed to be in course of enactment. His dog was howling, his head was aching fearfully—somebody was pulling him about, hands were loosening his neckerchief.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000807","text":"On opening his eyes he found that evening had sunk to dusk in a strange manner of unexpectedness.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000808","text":"The young girl with the remarkably pleasant lips and white teeth was beside him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000809","text":"More than this—astonishingly more—his head was upon her lap, his face and neck were disagreeably wet, and her fingers were unbuttoning his collar.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000810","text":"“Whatever is the matter?” said Oak, vacantly.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000811","text":"She seemed to experience mirth, but of too insignificant a kind to start enjoyment.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000812","text":"“Nothing now,” she answered, “since you are not dead. It is a wonder you were not suffocated in this hut of yours.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000813","text":"“Ah, the hut!” murmured Gabriel. “I gave ten pounds for that hut. But I’ll sell it, and sit under thatched hurdles as they did in old times, and curl up to sleep in a lock of straw! It played me nearly the same trick the other day!” Gabriel, by way of emphasis, brought down his fist upon the floor.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000814","text":"“It was not exactly the fault of the hut,” she observed in a tone which showed her to be that novelty among women—one who finished a thought before beginning the sentence which was to convey it. “You should, I think, have considered, and not have been so foolish as to leave the slides closed.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000815","text":"“Yes I suppose I should,” said Oak, absently.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000816","text":"He was endeavouring to catch and appreciate the sensation of being thus with her, his head upon her dress, before the event passed on into the heap of bygone things.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000817","text":"He wished she knew his impressions; but he would as soon have thought of carrying an odour in a net as of attempting to convey the intangibilities of his feeling in the coarse meshes of language.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000818","text":"She made him sit up, and then Oak began wiping his face and shaking himself like a Samson. “How can I thank ’ee?” he said at last, gratefully, some of the natural rusty red having returned to his face.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000819","text":"“Oh, never mind that,” said the girl, smiling, and allowing her smile to hold good for Gabriel’s next remark, whatever that might prove to be.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000820","text":"“I heard your dog howling and scratching at the door of the hut when I came to the milking (it was so lucky, Daisy’s milking is almost over for the season, and I shall not come here after this week or the next).","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000821","text":"The dog saw me, and jumped over to me, and laid hold of my skirt.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000822","text":"I came across and looked round the hut the very first thing to see if the slides were closed.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000823","text":"My uncle has a hut like this one, and I have heard him tell his shepherd not to go to sleep without leaving a slide open.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000824","text":"I opened the door, and there you were like dead.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000825","text":"I threw the milk over you, as there was no water, forgetting it was warm, and no use.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000826","text":"“I wonder if I should have died?” Gabriel said, in a low voice, which was rather meant to travel back to himself than to her.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000827","text":"“Oh no!” the girl replied. She seemed to prefer a less tragic probability; to have saved a man from death involved talk that should harmonise with the dignity of such a deed—and she shunned it.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000828","text":"“I believe you saved my life, Miss—I don’t know your name. I know your aunt’s, but not yours.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000829","text":"“I would just as soon not tell it—rather not. There is no reason either why I should, as you probably will never have much to do with me.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000830","text":"“Still, I should like to know.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000831","text":"“You can inquire at my aunt’s—she will tell you.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000832","text":"“And mine isn’t. You seem fond of yours in speaking it so decisively, Gabriel Oak.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000833","text":"“You see, it is the only one I shall ever have, and I must make the most of it.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000834","text":"“I always think mine sounds odd and disagreeable.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000835","text":"“I should think you might soon get a new one.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000836","text":"“Mercy!—how many opinions you keep about you concerning other people, Gabriel Oak.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000837","text":"“Well, Miss—excuse the words—I thought you would like them. But I can’t match you, I know, in mapping out my mind upon my tongue. I never was very clever in my inside. But I thank you. Come, give me your hand.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000838","text":"She hesitated, somewhat disconcerted at Oak’s old-fashioned earnest conclusion to a dialogue lightly carried on.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000839","text":"“Very well,” she said, and gave him her hand, compressing her lips to a demure impassivity.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000840","text":"He held it but an instant, and in his fear of being too demonstrative, swerved to the opposite extreme, touching her fingers with the lightness of a small-hearted person.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000841","text":"“I am sorry,” he said the instant after.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000842","text":"“Letting your hand go so quick.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000843","text":"“You may have it again if you like; there it is.” She gave him her hand again.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000844","text":"Oak held it longer this time—indeed, curiously long. “How soft it is—being winter time, too—not chapped or rough or anything!” he said.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000845","text":"“There—that’s long enough,” said she, though without pulling it away. “But I suppose you are thinking you would like to kiss it? You may if you want to.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000846","text":"“I wasn’t thinking of any such thing,” said Gabriel, simply; “but I will—”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000847","text":"“That you won’t!” She snatched back her hand.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000848","text":"Gabriel felt himself guilty of another want of tact.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000849","text":"“Now find out my name,” she said, teasingly; and withdrew.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000850","text":"CHAPTER IV GABRIEL’S RESOLVE—THE VISIT—THE MISTAKE","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000851","text":"The only superiority in women that is tolerable to the rival sex is, as a rule, that of the unconscious kind; but a superiority which recognizes itself may sometimes please by suggesting possibilities of capture to the subordinated man.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000852","text":"This well-favoured and comely girl soon made appreciable inroads upon the emotional constitution of young Farmer Oak.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000853","text":"His dog waited for his meals in a way so like that in which Oak waited for the girl’s presence, that the farmer was quite struck with the resemblance, felt it lowering, and would not look at the dog.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000854","text":"However, he continued to watch through the hedge for her regular coming, and thus his sentiments towards her were deepened without any corresponding effect being produced upon herself.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000855","text":"Oak had nothing finished and ready to say as yet, and not being able to frame love phrases which end where they begin; passionate tales—","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000856","text":"—Full of sound and fury, —Signifying nothing—","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000857","text":"By making inquiries he found that the girl’s name was Bathsheba Everdene, and that the cow would go dry in about seven days. He dreaded the eighth day.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000858","text":"The cow had ceased to give milk for that year, and Bathsheba Everdene came up the hill no more.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000859","text":"Gabriel had reached a pitch of existence he never could have anticipated a short time before.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000860","text":"He liked saying “Bathsheba” as a private enjoyment instead of whistling; turned over his taste to black hair, though he had sworn by brown ever since he was a boy, isolated himself till the space he filled in the public eye was contemptibly small.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000861","text":"Love is a possible strength in an actual weakness.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000862","text":"Marriage transforms a distraction into a support, the power of which should be, and happily often is, in direct proportion to the degree of imbecility it supplants.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000863","text":"Oak began now to see light in this direction, and said to himself, “I’ll make her my wife, or upon my soul I shall be good for nothing!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000864","text":"All this while he was perplexing himself about an errand on which he might consistently visit the cottage of Bathsheba’s aunt.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000865","text":"He found his opportunity in the death of a ewe, mother of a living lamb.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000866","text":"Hurst, the aunt—George, the dog walking behind, with a countenance of great concern at the serious turn pastoral affairs seemed to be taking.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000867","text":"Gabriel had watched the blue wood-smoke curling from the chimney with strange meditation.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000868","text":"He had made a toilet of a nicely-adjusted kind—of a nature between the carefully neat and the carelessly ornate—of a degree between fine-market-day and wet-Sunday selection.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000869","text":"Nothing disturbed the stillness of the cottage save the chatter of a knot of sparrows on the eaves; one might fancy scandal and rumour to be no less the staple topic of these little coteries on roofs than of those under them.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000870","text":"It seemed that the omen was an unpropitious one, for, as the rather untoward commencement of Oak’s overtures, just as he arrived by the garden gate, he saw a cat inside, going into various arched shapes and fiendish convulsions at the sight of his dog George.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000871","text":"A voice came from behind some laurel-bushes into which the cat had run:","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000872","text":"“Poor dear! Did a nasty brute of a dog want to kill it;—did he, poor dear!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000873","text":"“I beg your pardon,” said Oak to the voice, “but George was walking on behind me with a temper as mild as milk.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000874","text":"Almost before he had ceased speaking, Oak was seized with a misgiving as to whose ear was the recipient of his answer. Nobody appeared, and he heard the person retreat among the bushes.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000875","text":"Gabriel meditated, and so deeply that he brought small furrows into his forehead by sheer force of reverie.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000876","text":"Where the issue of an interview is as likely to be a vast change for the worse as for the better, any initial difference from expectation causes nipping sensations of failure.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000877","text":"Oak went up to the door a little abashed: his mental rehearsal and the reality had had no common grounds of opening.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000878","text":"“Will you tell Miss Everdene that somebody would be glad to speak to her?” said Mr.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000879","text":"(Calling one’s self merely Somebody, without giving a name, is not to be taken as an example of the ill-breeding of the rural world: it springs from a refined modesty, of which townspeople, with their cards and announcements, have no notion whatever.)","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000880","text":"Bathsheba was out. The voice had evidently been hers.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000881","text":"“Oh, thank ’ee,” said Gabriel, following her to the fireplace. “I’ve brought a lamb for Miss Everdene. I thought she might like one to rear; girls do.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000882","text":"“She might,” said Mrs. Hurst, musingly; “though she’s only a visitor here. If you will wait a minute, Bathsheba will be in.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000883","text":"“Yes, I will wait,” said Gabriel, sitting down. “The lamb isn’t really the business I came about, Mrs. Hurst. In short, I was going to ask her if she’d like to be married.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000884","text":"“Yes. Because if she would, I should be very glad to marry her. D’ye know if she’s got any other young man hanging about her at all?”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000885","text":"Hurst, poking the fire superfluously....","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000886","text":"“Yes—bless you, ever so many young men.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000887","text":"You see, Farmer Oak, she’s so good-looking, and an excellent scholar besides—she was going to be a governess once, you know, only she was too wild.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000888","text":"Not that her young men ever come here—but, Lord, in the nature of women, she must have a dozen!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000889","text":"“That’s unfortunate,” said Farmer Oak, contemplating a crack in the stone floor with sorrow. “I’m only an every-day sort of man, and my only chance was in being the first comer.... Well, there’s no use in my waiting, for that was all I came about: so I’ll take myself off home-along, Mrs. Hurst.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000890","text":"When Gabriel had gone about two hundred yards along the down, he heard a “hoi-hoi!” uttered behind him, in a piping note of more treble quality than that in which the exclamation usually embodies itself when shouted across a field.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000891","text":"He looked round, and saw a girl racing after him, waving a white handkerchief.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000892","text":"Oak stood still—and the runner drew nearer. It was Bathsheba Everdene. Gabriel’s colour deepened: hers was already deep, not, as it appeared, from emotion, but from running.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000893","text":"“Farmer Oak—I—” she said, pausing for want of breath pulling up in front of him with a slanted face and putting her hand to her side.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000894","text":"“I have just called to see you,” said Gabriel, pending her further speech.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000895","text":"“Yes—I know that,” she said panting like a robin, her face red and moist from her exertions, like a peony petal before the sun dries off the dew.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000896","text":"“I didn’t know you had come to ask to have me, or I should have come in from the garden instantly.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000897","text":"I ran after you to say—that my aunt made a mistake in sending you away from courting me—”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000898","text":"Gabriel expanded. “I’m sorry to have made you run so fast, my dear,” he said, with a grateful sense of favours to come. “Wait a bit till you’ve found your breath.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000899","text":"“—It was quite a mistake—aunt’s telling you I had a young man already,” Bathsheba went on. “I haven’t a sweetheart at all—and I never had one, and I thought that, as times go with women, it was _such_ a pity to send you away thinking that I had several.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000900","text":"“Really and truly I am glad to hear that!” said Farmer Oak, smiling one of his long special smiles, and blushing with gladness.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000901","text":"He held out his hand to take hers, which, when she had eased her side by pressing it there, was prettily extended upon her bosom to still her loud-beating heart.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000902","text":"Directly he seized it she put it behind her, so that it slipped through his fingers like an eel.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000903","text":"“I have a nice snug little farm,” said Gabriel, with half a degree less assurance than when he had seized her hand.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000904","text":"He went forward and stretched out his arm again.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000905","text":"Bathsheba had overtaken him at a point beside which stood a low stunted holly bush, now laden with red berries.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000906","text":"Seeing his advance take the form of an attitude threatening a possible enclosure, if not compression, of her person, she edged off round the bush.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000907","text":"“Why, Farmer Oak,” she said, over the top, looking at him with rounded eyes, “I never said I was going to marry you.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000908","text":"“Well—that _is_ a tale!” said Oak, with dismay. “To run after anybody like this, and then say you don’t want him!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000909","text":"Why, if I’d wanted you I shouldn’t have run after you like this; ’twould have been the _forwardest_ thing!","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000910","text":"But there was no harm in hurrying to correct a piece of false news that had been told you.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000911","text":"“Oh, no—no harm at all.” But there is such a thing as being too generous in expressing a judgment impulsively, and Oak added with a more appreciative sense of all the circumstances—“Well, I am not quite certain it was no harm.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000912","text":"“Indeed, I hadn’t time to think before starting whether I wanted to marry or not, for you’d have been gone over the hill.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000913","text":"“Come,” said Gabriel, freshening again; “think a minute or two. I’ll wait a while, Miss Everdene. Will you marry me? Do, Bathsheba. I love you far more than common!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000914","text":"“I’ll try to think,” she observed, rather more timorously; “if I can think out of doors; my mind spreads away so.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000915","text":"“Then give me time.” Bathsheba looked thoughtfully into the distance, away from the direction in which Gabriel stood.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000916","text":"“I can make you happy,” said he to the back of her head, across the bush. “You shall have a piano in a year or two—farmers’ wives are getting to have pianos now—and I’ll practise up the flute right well to play with you in the evenings.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000917","text":"“And have one of those little ten-pound gigs for market—and nice flowers, and birds—cocks and hens I mean, because they be useful,” continued Gabriel, feeling balanced between poetry and practicality.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000918","text":"“And a frame for cucumbers—like a gentleman and lady.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000919","text":"“And when the wedding was over, we’d have it put in the newspaper list of marriages.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000920","text":"“And the babies in the births—every man jack of ’em! And at home by the fire, whenever you look up, there I shall be—and whenever I look up there will be you.”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000921","text":"“Wait, wait, and don’t be improper!”","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000922","text":"Her countenance fell, and she was silent awhile. He regarded the red berries between them over and over again, to such an extent, that holly seemed in his after life to be a cypher signifying a proposal of marriage. Bathsheba decisively turned to him.","author":"The Buddha","source":"The Gospel of Buddha — Carus (1894)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000923","text":"Produced by Janet Blenkinship and the Online Distributed Proofreading Team at https://www.pgdp.net","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000924","text":"Author of \"Half-Hours with the Best American Authors,\" \"Tales from the Dramatists,\" etc.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000925","text":"Copyright, 1893, by J.B. Lippincott Company.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000926","text":"Copyright, 1904, by J.B. Lippincott Company.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000927","text":"Copyright, 1908, by J.B. Lippincott Company.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000928","text":"HERMANN, THE HERO OF GERMANY 7","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000929","text":"WITTEKIND, THE SAXON PATRIOT 37","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000930","text":"THE RAIDS OF THE SEA-ROVERS 47","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000931","text":"THE MISFORTUNES OF DUKE ERNST 64","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000932","text":"THE FORTUNES OF HENRY THE FOURTH 77","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000933","text":"THE ANECDOTES OF MEDIÆVAL GERMANY 92","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000934","text":"FREDERICK BARBAROSSA AND MILAN 105","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000935","text":"THE CRUSADE OF FREDERICK II 118","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000936","text":"THE FALL OF THE GHIBELLINES 129","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000937","text":"THE TRIBUNAL OF THE HOLY VEHM 138","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000938","text":"WILLIAM TELL AND THE SWISS PATRIOTS 148","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000939","text":"THE BLACK DEATH AND THE FLAGELLANTS 162","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000940","text":"SEMPACH AND ARNOLD WINKELRIED 187","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000941","text":"LUTHER AND THE INDULGENCES 217","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000942","text":"SOLYMAN THE MAGNIFICENT AT GUNTZ 229","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000943","text":"THE PEASANTS AND THE ANABAPTISTS 238","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000944","text":"THE FORTUNES OF WALLENSTEIN 252","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000945","text":"THE END OF TWO GREAT SOLDIERS 265","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000946","text":"THE YOUTH OF FREDERICK THE GREAT 288","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000947","text":"VOLTAIRE AND FREDERICK THE GREAT 305","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000948","text":"SCENES FROM THE SEVEN YEARS' WAR 315","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000949","text":"THE OLD EMPIRE AND THE NEW 343","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000950","text":"MAXIMILIAN RECEIVING VENETIAN DELEGATION 7","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000951","text":"RETURN OF HERMANN AFTER HIS VICTORY OVER THE ROMANS 13","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000952","text":"THE MOUSE-TOWER ON THE RHINE 61","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000953","text":"THUSNELDA IN THE GERMANICUS TRIUMPH 94","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000954","text":"STATUE OF ARNOLD WINKELRIED 193","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000955","text":"THE MOSQUE OF SOLYMAN, CONSTANTINOPLE 236","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000956","text":"THE PARLIAMENT HOUSE IN VIENNA 278","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000957","text":"STATUE OF FREDERICK THE GREAT, UNTER DEN LINDEN, BERLIN 289","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000958","text":"SANS SOUCI, PALACE OF FREDERICK THE GREAT 315","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000959","text":"THE LAST DAY OF ANDREAS HOFER 340","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000960","text":"[Illustration: MAXIMILIAN RECEIVING VENETIAN DELEGATION.]","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000961","text":"In the days of Augustus, the emperor of Rome in its golden age of prosperity, an earnest effort was made to subdue and civilize barbarian Germany.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000962","text":"Drusus, the step-son of the emperor, led the first army of invasion into this forest-clad land of the north, penetrating deeply into the country and building numerous forts to guard his conquests.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000963","text":"His last invasion took him as far as the Elbe.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000964","text":"Here, as we are told, he found himself confronted by a supernatural figure, in the form of a woman, who waved him back with lofty and threatening air, saying, \"How much farther wilt thou advance, insatiable Drusus?","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000965","text":"It is not thy lot to behold all these countries.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000966","text":"the term of thy deeds and of thy life is at hand.\" Drusus retreated, and died on his return.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000967","text":"Tiberius, his brother, succeeded him, and went far to complete the conquest he had begun.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000968","text":"Germany seemed destined to become a Roman province.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000969","text":"The work of conquest was followed by efforts to civilize the free-spirited barbarians, which, had they been conducted wisely, might have led to success.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000970","text":"One of the Roman governors, Sentius, prefect of the Rhine, treated the people so humanely that many of them adopted the arts and customs of Rome, and the work of overcoming their barbarism was well begun.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000971","text":"He was succeeded in this office by Varus, a friend and confidant of the emperor, but a man of very different character, and one who not only lacked military experience and mental ability, but utterly misunderstood the character of the people he was dealing with.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000972","text":"They might be led, they could not be driven into civilization, as the new prefect was to learn.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000973","text":"All went well as long as Varus remained peacefully in his head-quarters, erecting markets, making the natives familiar with the attractive wares of Rome, instructing them in civilized arts, and taking their sons into the imperial army.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000974","text":"All went ill when he sought to hasten his work by acts of oppression, leading his forces across the Weser into the land of the Cherusci, enforcing there the rigid Roman laws, and chastising and executing free-born Germans for deeds which in their creed were not crimes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000975","text":"Varus, who had at first made himself loved by his kindness, now made himself hated by his severity.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000976","text":"The Germans brooded over their wrongs, awed by the Roman army, which consisted of thirty thousand picked men, strongly intrenched, their camps being impregnable to their undisciplined foes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000977","text":"Yet the high-spirited barbarians felt that this army was but an entering wedge, and that, if not driven out, their whole country would gradually be subdued.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000978","text":"A patriot at length arose among the Cherusci, determined to free his country from the intolerable Roman yoke.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000979","text":"He was a handsome and athletic youth, Arminius, or Hermann as the Germans prefer to name him, of noble descent, and skilled alike in the arts of war and of oratory, his eloquence being equal to his courage.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000980","text":"He was one of the sons of the Germans who had served in the Roman armies, and had won there such distinction as to gain the honors of knighthood and citizenship.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000981","text":"Now, perceiving clearly the subjection that threatened his countrymen, and filled with an ardent love of liberty, he appeared among them, and quickly filled their dispirited souls with much of his own courage and enthusiasm.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000982","text":"At midnight meetings in the depths of the forests a conspiracy against Varus and his legions was planned, Hermann being the chosen leader of the perilous enterprise.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000983","text":"It was not long before this conspiracy was revealed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000984","text":"The German control over the Cherusci had been aided by Segestus, a treacherous chief, whose beautiful and patriotic daughter, Thusnelda, had given her hand in marriage to Hermann, against her father's will.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000985","text":"Filled with revengeful anger at this action, and hoping to increase his power, Segestus told the story of the secret meetings, which he had discovered, to Varus, and bade him beware, as a revolt against him might at any moment break out.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000986","text":"Pride in the Roman power and scorn of that of the Germans had deeply infected the mind of Varus, and he heard with incredulous contempt this story that the barbarians contemplated rising against the best trained legions of Rome.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000987","text":"Autumn came, the autumn of the year 9 A.D.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000988","text":"The long rainy season of the German forests began.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000989","text":"Hermann decided that the time had arrived for the execution of his plans.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000990","text":"He began his work with a deceitful skill that quite blinded the too-trusting Varus, inducing him to send bodies of troops into different parts of the country, some to gather provisions for the winter supply of the camps, others to keep watch over some tribes not yet subdued.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000991","text":"The Roman force thus weakened, the artful German succeeded in drawing Varus with the remainder of his men from their intrenchments, by inducing one of the subjected tribes to revolt.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000992","text":"The scheme of Hermann had, so far, been completely successful.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000993","text":"Varus, trusting to his representations, had weakened his force, and now prepared to draw the main body of his army out of camp.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000994","text":"Hermann remained with him to the last, dining with him the day before the starting of the expedition, and inspiring so much confidence in his faithfulness to Rome that Varus refused to listen to Segestus, who earnestly entreated him to take Hermann prisoner on the spot.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000995","text":"He even took Hermann's advice, and decided to march on the revolted tribe by a shorter than the usual route, oblivious to the fact that it led through difficult mountain passes, shrouded in forests and bordered by steep and rocky acclivities.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000996","text":"The treacherous plans of the patriotic German had fully succeeded.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000997","text":"While the Romans were toiling onward through the straitened passes, Hermann had sought his waiting and ambushed countrymen, to whom he gave the signal that the time for vengeance had come.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000998","text":"Then, as if the dense forests had borne a sudden crop of armed men, the furious barbarians poured out in thousands upon the unsuspecting legionaries.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-000999","text":"The mountain torrents, swollen by the downpour of rain, over--flowed their banks and invaded the passes, along which the Romans, encumbered with baggage, were wearily dragging onward in broken columns.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001000","text":"Only the discipline of the Romans saved them from speedy destruction.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001001","text":"With the instinct of their training they hastened to gather into larger bodies, and their resistance, at first feeble, soon became more effective.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001002","text":"The struggle continued until night-fall, by which time the surviving Romans had fought their way to a more open place, where they hastily intrenched.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001003","text":"But it was impossible for them to remain there.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001004","text":"Their provisions were lost or exhausted, thousands of foes surrounded them, and their only hope lay in immediate and rapid flight.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001005","text":"The soldiers had recovered somewhat from the fatigue of the day before.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001006","text":"Setting fire to what baggage remained in their hands, they began a retreat fighting as they went, for the implacable enemy disputed every step.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001007","text":"The first part of their route lay through an open plain, where they marched in orderly ranks.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001008","text":"But there were mountains still to pass, and they quickly found themselves in a wooded and pathless valley, in whose rugged depths defence was almost impossible.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001009","text":"Here they fell in thousands before the weapons of their foes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001010","text":"It was but a small body of survivors that at length escaped from that deadly defile and threw up intrenchments for the night in a more open spot.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001011","text":"With the dawn of the next day they resumed their progress, and were at no great distance from their stronghold of Aliso when they found their progress arrested by fresh tribes, who assailed them with murderous fury.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001012","text":"On they struggled, fighting, dying, marking every step of the route with their dead.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001013","text":"Varus, now reduced to despair, and seeing only slaughter or captivity before him, threw himself on his sword, and died in the midst of those whom his blind confidence had led to destruction.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001014","text":"Of the whole army only a feeble remnant reached Aliso, which fort they soon after abandoned and fought their way to the Rhine.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001015","text":"While this was going on, the detachments which Varus had sent out in various directions were similarly assailed, and met the same fate as had overtaken the main body of the troops.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001016","text":"[Illustration: RETURN OF HERMANN AFTER HIS VICTORY OVER THE ROMANS.]","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001017","text":"No more frightful disaster had ever befallen the Roman arms.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001018","text":"Many prisoners had been taken, among them certain judges and lawyers, who were the chief objects of Hermann's hate, and whom he devoted to a painful death.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001019","text":"He then offered sacrifices to the gods, to whom he consecrated the booty, the slain, and the leading prisoners, numbers of them being slain on the altars of his deities.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001020","text":"These religious ceremonies completed, the prisoners who still remained were distributed among the tribes as slaves.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001021","text":"The effort of Varus to force Roman customs and laws upon the Germans had led to a fearful retribution.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001022","text":"When the news of this dreadful event reached Rome, that city was filled with grief and fear.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001023","text":"The heart of Augustus, now an old man, was stricken with dismay at the slaughter of the best soldiers of the empire.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001024","text":"With neglected dress and person he wandered about the rooms and halls of the palace, his piteous appeal, \"Varus, give me back my legions!\" showing how deeply the disaster had pierced his soul.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001025","text":"Hasty efforts were at once made to prevent the possible serious consequences of the overthrow of the slain legions.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001026","text":"The Romans on the Rhine intrenched themselves in all haste.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001027","text":"The Germans in the imperial service were sent to distant provinces, and recruits were raised in all parts of the country, their purpose being to protect Gaul from an invasion by the triumphant tribes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001028","text":"Yet so great was the fear inspired by the former German onslaughts, and by this destructive outbreak, that only threats of death induced the Romans to serve.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001029","text":"As it proved, this defensive activity was not needed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001030","text":"The Germans, satisfied, as it seemed, with expelling the Romans from their country, destroyed their forts and military roads, and settled back into peace, with no sign of a desire to cross the Rhine.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001031","text":"For six years peace continued.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001032","text":"Augustus died, and Tiberius became emperor of Rome.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001033","text":"Then, in the year 14 A.D., an effort was made to reconquer Germany, an army commanded by the son of Drusus, known to history under the name of Germanicus, attacking the Marsi, when intoxicated and unarmed after a religious feast.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001034","text":"Great numbers of the defenceless tribesmen were slain, but the other tribes sprung to arms and drove the invader back across the Rhine.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001035","text":"In the next year Hermann was again brought into the fray.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001036","text":"Segestus had robbed him of his wife, the beautiful patriot Thusnelda, who hitherto had been his right hand in council in his plans against the Roman foe.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001037","text":"Hermann besieged Segestus to regain possession of his wife, and pressed the traitor so closely that he sent his son Sigismund to Germanicus, who was again on the German side of the Rhine, imploring aid.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001038","text":"The Roman leader took instant advantage of this promising opportunity.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001039","text":"He advanced and forced Hermann to raise the siege, and himself took possession of Thusnelda, who was destined soon afterwards to be made the leading feature in a Roman triumph.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001040","text":"Segestus was rewarded for his treason, and was given lands in Gaul, his life being not safe among the people he had betrayed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001041","text":"As for the daughter whom he had yielded to Roman hands, her fate troubled little his base soul.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001042","text":"Thusnelda is still a popular character in German legend, there being various stories extant concerning her.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001043","text":"One of these relates that, when she lay concealed in the old fort of Schellenpyrmont, she was warned by the cries of a faithful bird of the coming of the Romans, who were seeking stealthily to approach her hiding-place.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001044","text":"The loss of his beloved wife roused Hermann's heroic spirit, and spread indignation among the Germans, who highly esteemed the noble-hearted consort of their chief.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001045","text":"They rose hastily in arms, and Hermann was soon at the head of a large army, prepared to defend his country against the invading hosts of the Romans.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001046","text":"But as the latter proved too strong to face in the open field, the Germans retreated with their families and property, the country left by them being laid waste by the advancing legions.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001047","text":"Germanicus soon reached the scene of the late slaughter, and caused the bones of the soldiers of Varus to be buried.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001048","text":"But in doing this he was obliged to enter the mountain defiles in which the former army had met its fate.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001049","text":"Hermann and his men watched the Romans intently from forest and hilltop.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001050","text":"When they had fairly entered the narrow valleys, the adroit chief appeared before them at the head of a small troop, which retreated as if in fear, drawing them onward until the whole army had entered the pass.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001051","text":"Then the fatal signal was given, and the revengeful Germans fell upon the legionaries of Germanicus as they had done upon those of Varus, cutting them down in multitudes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001052","text":"But Germanicus was a much better soldier than Varus.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001053","text":"He succeeded in extricating the remnant of his men, after they had lost heavily, and in making an orderly retreat to his ships, which awaited him upon the northern coast whence he had entered the country.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001054","text":"There were two other armies, one of which had invaded Germany from the coast of Friesland, and was carried away by a flood, narrowly escaping complete destruction.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001055","text":"The third had entered from the Rhine.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001056","text":"This was overtaken by Hermann while retreating over the long bridges which the Romans had built across the marshes of Münsterland, and which were now in a state of advanced decay.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001057","text":"Here it found itself surrounded by seemingly insuperable dangers, being, in part of its route, shut up in a narrow dell, into which the enemy had turned the waters of a rapid stream.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001058","text":"While defending their camp, the waters poured upon the soldiers, rising to their knees, and a furious tempest at the same time burst over their heads.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001059","text":"Yet discipline, again prevailed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001060","text":"They lost heavily, but succeeded in cutting their way through their enemies and reaching the Rhine.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001061","text":"In the next year, 17 A.D., Germanicus again invaded Germany, sailing with a thousand ships through the northern seas and up the Ems.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001062","text":"Flavus, the brother of Hermann, who had remained in the service of Rome, was with him, and addressed his patriotic brother from the river-side, seeking to induce him to desert the German cause, by painting in glowing colors the advantage of being a Roman citizen.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001063","text":"Hermann, furious at his desertion of his country, replied to him with curses, as the only language worthy to use to a traitor, and would have ridden across the stream to kill him, but that he was held back by his men.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001064","text":"A battle soon succeeded, the Germans falling into an ambuscade artfully laid by the Roman leader, and being defeated with heavy loss.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001065","text":"Germanicus raised a stately monument on the spot, as a memorial of his victory.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001066","text":"The sight of this Roman monument in their country infuriated the Germans, and they attacked the Romans again, this time with such fury, and such slaughter on both sides, that neither party was able to resume the fight when the next day dawned.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001067","text":"Germanicus, who had been very severely handled, retreated to his ships and set sail.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001068","text":"On his voyage the heavens appeared to conspire against him.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001069","text":"A tempest arose in which most of the vessels were wrecked and many of the legionaries lost.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001070","text":"When he returned to Rome, shortly afterwards, a fort on the Taunus was the only one which Rome possessed in Germany.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001071","text":"Hermann had cleared his country of the foe.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001072","text":"Yet Germanicus was given a triumph, in which Thusnelda walked, laden with chains, to the capitol.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001073","text":"The remaining events in the life of this champion of German liberty were few.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001074","text":"While the events described had been taking place in the north of Germany, there were troubles in the south.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001075","text":"Here a chieftain named Marbodius, who, like Hermann, had passed his youth in the Roman armies, was the leader of several powerful tribes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001076","text":"He lacked the patriotism of Hermann, and sought to ally himself with the Romans, with the hope of attaining to supreme power in Germany.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001077","text":"Hermann sought to rouse patriotic sentiments in his mind, but in vain, and the movements of Marbodius having revealed his purposes, a coalition was formed against him, with Hermann at its head.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001078","text":"He was completely defeated, and southern Germany saved from Roman domination, as the northern districts had already been.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001079","text":"Peace followed, and for several years Hermann remained general-in-chief of the German people, and the acknowledged bulwark of their liberties.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001080","text":"But envy arose; he was maligned, and accused of aiming at sovereignty, as Marbodius had done; and at length his own relations, growing to hate and fear him, conspired against and murdered him.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001081","text":"Thus ignobly fell the noblest of the ancient Germans, the man whose patriotism saved the realm of the Teutonic tribes from becoming a province of the empire of Rome.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001082","text":"Had not Hermann lived, the history of Europe might have pursued a different course, and the final downfall of the colossus of the south been long averted, Germany acting as its bulwark of defence instead of becoming the nursery of its foes.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001083","text":"Of the Teutonic invaders of Italy none are invested with more interest than the Lombards,--the Long Beards, to give them their original title.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001084","text":"Legend yields us the story of their origin, a story of interest enough to repeat.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001085","text":"A famine had been caused in Denmark by a great flood, and the people, to avoid danger of starvation, had resolved to put all the old men and women to death, in order to save the food for the young and strong.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001086","text":"This radical proposition was set aside through the advice of a wise woman, named Gambara, who suggested that lots should be drawn for the migration of a third of the population.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001087","text":"Her counsel was taken and the migration began, under the leadership of her two sons.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001088","text":"These migrants wore beards of prodigious length, whence their subsequent name.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001089","text":"They first entered the land of the Vandals, who refused them permission to settle.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001090","text":"This was a question to be decided at sword's point, and war was declared.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001091","text":"Both sides appealed to the gods for aid, Gambara praying to Freya, while the Vandals invoked Odin, who answered that he would grant the victory to the party he should first behold at the dawn of the coming day.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001092","text":"In front of the Danish host were stationed their women, who had loosened their long hair, and let it hang down over their faces.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001093","text":"Who are these with long beards?\" demanded Odin, on seeing these Danish amazons.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001094","text":"This settled the question of victory, and also gave the invaders a new name, that of Longobardi,--due, in this legend, to the long hair of the women instead of the long beards of the men.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001095","text":"There are other legends, but none worth repeating.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001096","text":"The story of their king Alboin, with whom we have particularly to deal, begins, however, with a story which may be in part legendary.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001097","text":"They were now in hostile relations with the Gepidæ, the first nation to throw off the yoke of the Huns.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001098","text":"Alboin, son of Audoin, king of the Longobardi, killed Thurismund, son of Turisend, king of the Gepidæ, in battle, but forgot to carry away his arms, and thus returned home without a trophy of his victory.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001099","text":"In consequence, his stern father refused him a seat at his table, as one unworthy of the honor.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"},{"id":"zen-ext-001100","text":"Such was the ancient Lombard custom, and it must be obeyed.","author":"Various (Zen)","source":"Buddhist Scriptures — Burnouf (1880)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:impermanence","theme:mindfulness","theme:mindfulness,impermanence","tradition:buddhism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain text"}]}